Comment: Ruckmen hit their peak in their 7th season, and we saw Gawn (111) and Grundy (130) stamp themselves as stars of the comp in theirs. English's 7th season was every bit as good. After a breakout 2022, English went to another level in 2023, averaging 128 and, more importantly, played every game of the season. Both Gawn and Grundy improved their average in the year following their first season averaging 125+ and we typically see greater consistency in the top ruck tier than the other positions. That's why it's historically proved beneficial to pay up in the ruck (#setandforget) as they often back it up. However, with Gawn, Grundy and Xerri all stepping into solo roles this season, it's a rare year that we have multiple appealing ruck options with significant price upside. I think I'd pass on English to start the season and hope that one of the other options closes the gap significantly.
Short: No reason why he won't lead the comp in scoring again, although lingering concussion issues and Gawndy freed means there might be better value in the ruck this year

Comment: The Bont has always been a player of contention amongst SuperCoaches, given his favourable stats breakdown (above the top eight average for contested rate, tackles, goals and goal assists), but he took his game to a new level in 2023, playing a full time mid role after the departure of Josh Dunkley. With Oliver's interrupted last nine months, he's my pick to be the number one scorer again and a safe M1, despite his top price-tag. I normally look for value in all my picks, but I'm considering making an exception for Bont to be my perma Captain.
Short: The number one player IRL and SC, at 28 he could very well go back-to-back

Comment: We got the solo Marshall we wished for in 2023 and didn't he deliver - a 114 average, including 134 in his last five and 160 in finals. He is a genuine stat-stuffer, however he kicks the ball more than the average ruck, which sees him have higher clangers and lower disposal efficiency. Now with Gawn and Grundy separated, I doubt Marshall will be a top two ruck again in 2024, but he should provide similar output to what he did last season if he remains the solo ruck.
Short: With Gawn and Grundy separated, I doubt Marshall will be a top two ruck again in 2024, but he should provide similar output to what he did post-bye last season (118)

Comment: Oliver has been a SuperCoach stud for the majority of his career, averaging over 120 in each of his last four seasons. His perfect SC combo of high CBAs, TOG and contested possession rate makes him the logical challenge to Bont for M1. However, his off-season has been much documented and while I think he'll bounce back and have a point to prove, paying that price-tag as a starting pick you need everything to go right.
Short: The logical challenge to Bont for M1, but his much documented off-season and early bye makes him a risky play

Comment: After breaking out in his first season at the Crows, Dawson moved into the midfield in his second season and went to another level, averaging 116 from 70% CBAs. He looked a natural in there, doing everything from tackling, winning the clearance and bobbing up to take his marks. He's now lost his defender status but keeps his relevance, as he comes into 2024 as the 7th most expensive midfielder. The Crows continue to recruit forwards and defenders, so Dawson is expected to keep his role in 2024 and put up top eight numbers again. But after the initial jump in average from changing clubs and then again from changing role, has he got any more upside left in him?
Short: Lost his defender status but still relevant in his role as an everywhere man

Comment: Zach Merrett isn't your typical elite SuperCoach mid. He has a low contested possession rate of 34% (compared to the other top eight mids of 45%), however his kicking efficiency, arguably the best short kick in the competition, helps him produce top eight numbers. He matched a career best 116 in 2023, thanks to an increase in pressure acts and standing up in big moments. He's always been subject and vulnerable to a tag, but 112+ in each of his last four seasons suggest he can now push through. A safe bet to remain at that level again, but I'm wanting a bit more upside (price and points) for my starting mids.
Short: 112+ in each of his last four seasons, despite the weekly tag threat and low contested possession rate

Comment: Gulden's 2023 breakout will go down as one of the best in SuperCoach. 84 to 112, an increase of 28 points per game. And he didn't do it in the conventional manner of bulk CBAs and high tackle numbers. He displayed the perfect mix of inside and outside which saw him score high and consistently in all situations. Given how damaging he was, you'd expect more attention to come his way in 2024. However, at just 21, he's only going to be better and a potential top eight mid for the next decade. In terms of starting squad, the high price and early bye puts a line through him for me.
Short: Perfect inside/outside balance will make him a top SuperCoach player for the next decade

Comment: Taranto finally got the full time mid role he and SuperCoaches have been calling for, jumping to 77% in his first season at the Tigers, compared to an average of 49% in his prior three seasons at the Giants. And he got off to a flyer, averaging 119 pre-bye which far exceeded my expectations. He came back to earth post-bye, averaging 87, which resulted in a 107 average. He can find the ball and tackles well (averaged more disposals and tackles than the top eight mids in SuperCoach), however his disposal efficiency (59% v 72%) and clanger numbers (5.3 v 3.6) makes it nearly impossible for him to score premium numbers consistently. These are two metrics that are hard to reverse, as they are not role dependent, so I double we'll see Taranto in our SuperCoach sides again now that he has lost his forward status.
Short: 119/87 pre/post-bye splits crazy, but his low kicking efficiency will see him be more on the lower end of that range more often than not

Comment: After steadily improving in each of his three seasons, Green genuinely arrived in 2023. With Hopper and Taranto gone, Green went from 58% CBAs to 84% and boosted his average by 24 points. There were no concerns about his scoring potential, as even in his early year he displayed the contested and disposal rate of a top eight SuperCoach mid. Personally, I believe he's the most likely of the top eight mids to improve on his starting price in 2024 and one I'm eying off as my M1 for 2024. The Round 3 bye is my only concern but North and WC first up might make up for that.
Short: A natural ball winner now playing the right role and at 23, he's only getting better

Comment: Brayshaw is a player who is better in real life than his SuperCoach scoring suggests. This is largely due to the fact that he's not much of a contested footballer, despite his one percenters and effort. He wins 33% of his possessions contested (the top eight mids averaged 45%) and averaged four clearances per game (Oliver, Bont, Libba and Neale are all 7+). Contested possessions are gold in SuperCoach, however he still managed 114 post-bye and 122 in the L5 without them. He's still just 24, so there's every chance Brayshaw will improve his contested game. He's underpriced, has potential to be a top eight and no early bye, so he's starting to tick some boxes.
Short: 3 x 107+ seasons in a row, but low contested numbers have kept him behind the top 8, 122 in L5 of 2023 shows he can do it though

Comment: Laird has been a gun his entire career, but has become an elite SuperCoacher of the past three seasons since moving into the middle. He slowed down a bit last season, dropping 11 points per game, largely due to Jordan Dawson becoming the number one man in there. That will likely continue, so while I still have Laird as a top eight mid for 2024, I doubt we'll see him hit the heights of 2022 again.
Short: Has averaged 120 since moving in the middle in 2020

Comment: We haven't seen a SuperCoach prodigy like him. Excluding the Finn game which finished his H&A season, he averaged 120, starting as a running half-back and finishing as a midfielder. The tag threat will always be there, but I have him improving again to be the clear D1 for 2024. With the early bye and Finn lined up for Round 4, he's an upgrade target for me after his bye. But it's almost a matter of D1 by how much, so he doesn't have to outperform his price as much as other positions to prove a worthy selection.
Short: The clear D1 for 2024 and every chance to be the M1 of 2025

Comment: After being a tease in SuperCoach ever since he averaged 81 in his debut year, Serong broke out in 2023 to be a top-line midfielder IRL and SuperCoach. It's no question midfielders rely on CBAs for scoring and Serong hit the 80%+ mark in both CBAs and TOG, the combo we see with the top SC mids. With the role upside exhausted, he'll need to rely on natural development to improve again, something that should happen given he's still just 23. His outside game (3.3 marks per game v top eight mids of 4.1) is an area of improvement that should come with another pre-season under his belt as will his inside game, where he's already one of the best in the comp. A safe bet as a young top 10 mid.
Short: Arrived in 2023 with a boost in CBAs and TOG, at 23 his inside work should only get better and he'll challenge the top eight for the next five years

Comment: Parish has the attributes to be a top-line SuperCoach asset. He is a genuine ball magnet and with all the attention going to Merrett, he's never in danger of a tag. He also wins more contested possessions than many think, more than the average top eight mid. However, his kicking efficiency and clangers let him down, along with over two tackles less than the top eight mids. He'll need to pick these up to challenge the top 8, and while I think he'll get close, I think he lacks the class to be a top eight lock that you'd want at this price point.
Short: Ball magnet who avoids the tag, that's what I like from my SuperCoach mids, just needs to clean up his kicking

Comment: Petracca's SuperCoach game historically came with inconsistency. However, he put that to bed in 2023 with 21 scores over 100 and 10 over 120. Even more impressively, he did that with just 61% CBAs in a mid/fwd role. With Melbourne's forward woes, there is always a chance this split will continue. Melbourne's midfield is also looking rather thin, so if it doesn't however, we could see him challenge to be the best player in SuperCoach in 2024.
Short: Managed 119 despite the forward split, could go another level if full time mid but that's no guarantee with Melbourne's forward woes

Comment: The breakouts of 2023 continued, with Rozee bumping his average 13 on the back of his first season as a full time mid. He certainly has Fantasy IQ to him, running hard for cheap marks, which we love. However, he's going to need to up his contested game to remain relevant in SuperCoach now that he's lost his forward status. He averaged just 33% of his possessions contest, below the top eight mid average of 46%. In addition, his efficiency is also below the top eight which is not a great combo. His contested rate will improve with age and the captaincy, but it's why he'll likely be a level below the top eight in SuperCoach this season.
Short: MID-only and a low contested rate means he'll likely be a level below the top eight in SuperCoach

Comment: Been a gun IRL, but always lagged in efficiency and contested rate, which has kept a lid on his SC scoring. Add the fact he's been restricted by soft tissue injuries, being 31 and in a stacked midfield, it's not something I want to take a risk on.
Short: 31 with soft tissue issues, pass for me despite his decent history

Comment: Sicily is a genuine one of a kind in SuperCoach. His ability to find space and accumulate marks and kicks as a key position defender is remarkable. Disposal efficiency (83%) and intercepts (9.4 per game) are SuperCoach gold and it's why he'll remain a top two defender in 2024. The issue is he doesn't just get cheap possessions, his intercept and kicking ability is as good as there is, making him a vital cog in the Hawks system. Why wouldn't you tag him if you were an opposition coach? That's the only thing holding him back from being D1, but I still think he'll be around the mark in 2024.
Short: Opposition attention is the only thing holding him back from being D1, making him a high risk/reward pick

Comment: Typically, we want our players to get increases in CBAs. However, when you have multiple 110+ seasons as a defender, then a move to the midfield may not be a good thing. Docherty averaged a career high 22% CBAs in 2023, which increased as Blues went on their winning streak in the second half of the season. Playing in the midfield means a reduction in disposal efficiency and intercepts, two areas that make elite SuperCoach defenders. Unfortunately, he didn't substitute this with a material increase in contested possessions. He's lost his defender status as a result, and a 101 average as a MID-only will leave him well short of the top 8. If he moves back to defence, we know he's capable of being a top six defender, but I'd need to position change to occur before taking the leap.
Short: Will need to move back into defence to get back to being a Best 22 Fantasy asset

Comment: We all knew Dunkley can score as well as any player in SuperCoach. He averaged 118 in the last five games of 2018, 127 in the last half of 2019 and 116 in the first half of 2021. However, he just never put together a full season, largely due to Bevo taking him out of the midfield. The move to the Lions saw the full seasons as a midfielder eventuate, with 81% CBAs across the year. He's lost his forward status which has always been his big appeal, but I have a feeling he pushes the 120 mark in his second season in the Lions' system.
Short: 115 average was great, but given he finally had the full time mid role, I expected even higher - maybe it will come in 2024

Comment: Crouch's SuperCoach game has never emulated his Fantasy game, where he has regularly pushed the top eight mids. He was the 19th ranked mid in Fantasy in 2023, yet the 40th in SuperCoach, largely due to his below average disposal efficiency and contested rate. This has been a common theme throughout his career. 2022 he was ranked 8th in AFL Fantasy, yet 20th in SuperCoach. In 2019 he averaged 108 AFL Fantasy points and just 98 SuperCoach. His game isn't conducive to SuperCoach scoring and for that reason I can't have him in my team.
Short: Always been a better in Fantasy than SuperCoach

Comment: The much-loved Bulldog was the real winner of the Dunkley trade. He wound back the clock to average 116, making him comfortable a top eight midfielder, thanks to his elite contested rate (54%!) and disposal efficiency. Excluding his concussion game, he averaged 121! Libba was the preferred midfielder over Smith and Macrae. I think his role is safe, which is a big call for a midfielder coached by Bevo, which means he's going to be in top eight calculations again. I rather my premium mids being under 30, particularly when they come in fully priced.
Short: The real winner of the Dunkley trade, averaging 121 excl his concussion game

Comment: Nank has been a consistent ruck since arriving at the Tigers, averaging between 89 and 98 in five of the past six seasons, but put up career best numbers in 2023 to average over 100 for the first time. That ranked him 7th amongst rucks, so he's still a level below the top ones.
Short: Career best numbers in 2023 but still a level below the top rucks in SuperCoach

Comment: Sinclair proved his 8th year breakout was no fluke, putting up a 106 average following his 114 in 2022. He features the dream combo of CBAs and KIs, so he's always involved in the play. The CBAs reduced as in the second half of the season when Jack Steele returned, and it was here where he hit the 2022 heights, 113 post-bye and 116 in L5. That makes it back-to-back top six seasons, and given he's averaged 114 for 3/4 of that time, he might be slightly underpriced coming in at a 107 price-tag.
Short: Averaged 114 for 3/4 of the last two seasons, that's good enough to be a safe top six defender

Comment: Leon out meant Cogs got the mid-time he and SuperCoaches were craving, averaging 79% CBAs after being under 50% the prior two seasons. He went on to have a solid season, averaging 103, but didn't have the huge uptick that we saw from the other 'forwards' of Taranto, Gulden, Butters and Rozee. He's never been a great SuperCoach scorer, given his lower than 'top 8' average contested rate (36% v 45%) and disposal efficiency (68% v 72%). That's not a great combo, and while his role is favourable, it's unlikely he'll score enough to consider now that he's lost his forward status.
Short: Back in the middle but low contested rate and efficiency keeps a cap on his scoring

Comment: While Anderson continued to improve his SuperCoach output (77 to 84 to 100 to 105) his 2023 season was a frustrating one. He got off to a horrific start, averaging 85 in his first three games and went completely missing in games. Certainly not what I expected of a 22 year-old, former top two pick in his 4th season. He then got going, averaging 133 in his next five to be the form player in Fantasy. Just when I thought my bullish pre-season opinion of him was justified, he averaged 83 in his next 3. The remained up and down all season, which is what you get from an inside midfielder who gets below average tackle numbers (more than three less per game than the top eight mids) and kicks more than the elite SuperCoach mids which hurts his efficiency. I think he has the ability to become a 110-averaging midfielder, but I'll need to see a boost in tackle ability before being confident enough to jump on. Hardwick at the helm, whose system is not conducive to high SuperCoach scoring, adds to the hesitation.
Short: Has the ability to become a 110-averaging midfielder, but I'll need to see a boost in tackle ability to limit his inconsistency

Comment: Viney is a pure inside midfielder and a gun in real life, but doesn't get enough easy ball. Add in the fact he goes at 60% efficiency and five clangers a game, you can see why his career best SuperCoach season is 100. That's not enough to consider.
Short: Had a boost when Oliver was out, but it's very hard for a third option mid to average over 110+ and be a keeper he needs to be at that price

Comment: It was apparent from early in his career that Butters was going to be a star of the comp one day. It has meant a lot of SuperCoaches (none more than me) were burnt a few times backing him in for a breakout. However, that breakout came in 2023. He started slow following an AC injury in the pre-season, averaging 84 in his first four games. From there he exploded, averaging 120 the rest of the way. He displayed a perfect blend of inside and outside and should only improve his tackle game as he gets stronger and spends more time in the middle. His craft with the ball in hand is SuperCoach gold, as he wins it contested but then has great impact by foot. Like the other gun forwards of the 2023 season, he's lost his forward status. However, as a MID-only who is priced at 114 but averaged 120 when he got going, he's got the price and points upside to still be a viable starting pick this season.
Short: Averaged 120 when he got going last year and should only improve as he gets stronger and more experienced

Comment: Ryan has been a consistent SuperCoach defender for a number of seasons now, averaging over 100 across his past five seasons. However, he had a career best 2023, thanks to leading the comp in kicks per game, rebound 50s per game and 4th for marks. However, Freo's slow ball movement and kick-mark nature was criticised and I expect them to speed things up a bit in 2024, meaning less chances for easy plus-6ers for Ryan. While I still have him as a top 10 defender, he might have maxed out in 2023.
Short: 2 x 107+ seasons in last 4, we have to start taking him seriously as a top six defender

Comment: After looking like a future stud when he averaged 104 in his second season, Kelly finally returned close to that mark in 2023. Considering how bad West Coast were, he had an incredible season. As good as he was in his second season (All-Australian) and last year (Best & Fairest), he still couldn't average over 104, largely due to his below average efficiency (62%), marks (3 per game) and tackles (5 per game). It's been a trend his career to date and I doubt we'll see him push to the 110+ average required to be a SuperCoach-relevant midfielder.
Short: Great season but lacks the efficiency, marks and tackles to become an uber premium SuperCoach mid and a pre-season hamstring injury doesn't help

Comment: After displaying flashes of SuperCoach brilliance throughout his career, Newman exploded at the end of 2023 to average 111 post-bye and 124 L5, making him the 2nd best defender in that time. It certainly helped that Williams was out for the season and Docherty spent more time in the midfield, however he still had Saad being the main free runner back there and Newman was forced to play defensive matchups most weeks. This made his breakout season at age 30 even more impressive. It's hard to go against him based on what he produced, but with Williams returning and Docherty likely to spend more time down back, I think he'll score more in line with where he was pre-bye (92) rather than the 111 post.
Short: The second best defender in the game to finish 2023, but Williams returning and Doch potentially down there, I can't see him replicating it

Comment: After averaging 110+ three seasons in a row (including 2x 120+), Steele was one of the more disappointing players in Fantasy in 2023. He certainly had excuses, breaking his collarbone after Round 2 and arguably returning too early, missing just three weeks. He scored under 100 in eight of his next 10. Adding to the AC joint, he also tweaked his MCL and continued to play and was also rumoured to have a sore Achillies. He looked more like the Steele of old to finish the season, averaging 128 from Round 17 to 20, but he finished the season with a 57, 81 and 80 in his last 4. There is no question his 2023 season (and 2024 price) was impacted by injury. The issue was more how he looked when healthy. The Saints are trying to inject speed into their play and Steele looked a step off the pace at times. I think the days of him being a top few SuperCoach mid are over, but with an injury free season, he should return to at least 110+ which would be enough for him to be an okay starting pick, but you really need him to go 115 to be a keeper at that price.
Short: Plenty of excuses after 3x110+ seasons in a row, the game is a bit quicker now but if injury free should push back towards that 110+ mark

Comment: With a new coach and Hopper & Taranto to the Tigers, Kelly spend more time in the midfield in 2023. He was back to his best, averaging 116 pre-bye, enough to push the top eight mids. However, he didn't hit the CBA and scoring heights I expected of him post-bye, averaging just 86. It was a combination of being pushed to a wing on the back of Green's emergence, Coniglio's bounce back and the evergreen Cal Ward being the preferred as the inside mids (CBAs down to 51% from 63%) and a 23 (yes, 23) when Finned. His season also included a concussion and a hamstring. As much as he has all the tools to be a top eight mid and shown for periods of time that he can be, he just lets us down too often and he's someone I struggle to trust in SuperCoach.
Short: 115+ in 2019, 2020 and pre-bye 2023 shows he can be an elite mid in this game, but throw in a concussion, hamstring, a 23(!) and reducing CBAs highlights how hard he is to trust in this game

Comment: LDU's has all the attributes of a SuperCoach stud - high contested rate and high disposal efficiency - both above the rate of the average top eight mid. His 2023 was inconsistent, much like his career to date. The former number four pick started with a bang, 143 and 155 in his first two matches. He was then a late withdrawal in Round 3, returning in Round 4 but was a shadow of the player in the early rounds. He then missed five games for injury. However, after following a 94 first up from injury, he put up 126 in his next 6. He then was a late withdrawal (again) in Round 23 and we didn't see him again. He's an emerging star of the comp and I think we'll see him go to another level again this season. The only thing that I see holding him back is the potential for opposition attention as he's clearly the Roos' best player. Priced at 114, you can't afford him to be too inconsistent as you're picking him to be a top eight lock. And while there might be some downs amongst the ups for LDU in 2024, I think he can get to the top eight level.
Short: 126 in his last six games shows he's ready to mix it with the best, but given how damaging he is IRL, the tag threat will likely keep him in check

Comment: Noone saw Sheezel's debut season coming. The crafty 'forward' spent most of his time in defence and genuinely looked like Daicos in his first season, taking kick-ins and setting up play. He did have stints up forward and in the middle though, given the Roos were playing for development. He scored his best when he had the 'Daicos' role. In the 14 games over 100, he averaged 30% KI. The seven below 90 it was 13%. With no Aaron Hall and Jack Ziebell, Sheezel should have the green light to be the main man back there this season and we could see a 'Daicos-like' second year breakout. However, the Roos are still in development and might want to see how he goes in the middle or forward, where he excelled as a junior. Worth monitoring over the pre-season to see if he remains down back, and if so jump on.
Short: Daicos 2.0? Sounds like he'll be more mid/fwd which might cap his scoring, but if he returns to the half-back role look out

Comment: Considering he won a Brownlow, Neale had a very underwhelming SuperCoach season. In fact, he averaged his least amount of disposals since 2014 - including 2020 which had 16 minute quarters. He finished with an average of 108, making him the 17th best mid in Fantasy, failing to reach 100 on 12 occasions (2022 just five times). He's a proven SuperCoach scorer in the past, averaging 123 in 2022 and a league leading 134 in 2020. The issue with Neale is that he is clearly Brisbane's most damaging midfielder and teams quickly learnt that if they shut down Neale, they would shut down the Lions. The Lions know this and made a point to spread the load more in 2023, aided by the recruitment of Josh Dunkley. I imagine will see much the same in 2024, however his contested (52%) and efficiency (75%) combination is almost unmatched, so if he can get a few more disposals in 2024 he should return to be a top eight mid again.
Short: Despite the Brownlow, was the 17th ranked mid in SuperCoach with Lions looking to spread the load more

Comment: We began to see the best of the former Pick 5 in 2023. The natural on-baller, who averaged 115 AFL Fantasy points in NAB League, 10 more than ex-teammate Andrew Brayshaw in the same team, scored over 130 three weeks in a row from Round 6 to Round 8. He went on to surpass 125 four more times in his next eight games, before injury struck and he missed four of the final six matches. As much as I think he has a great SuperCoach game in him, playing as the 4th mid behind Cripps, Walsh and Hewett, means there will be some low games in there. I think it will happen one day, but I doubt that it will be while Cripps and Hewett are still around as the inside bulls.
Short: A hat-trick of 130s shows he has what it takes, but 4th in line at the Blues makes it hard to be a top eight mid in SuperCoach

Comment: Duggan had a career best SuperCoach season, averaging 90. He had a nice combo of CBAs and KI, joining the likes of Jordan Dawson, Nick Daicos and Harry Sheezel - all SuperCoach gems. However, he was a long way behind those names and I doubt he'll be required in the midfield as much in 2023 following the recruits, and I doubt West Coast will be as bad, meaning there won't be as much ball back there. I can't see him improving to be a top six in 2024.
Short: Career best 2023 but still a long way short

Comment: Stewart has been a SuperCoach stud for a number of seasons now, and he had his most consistent one in 2023. He averaged 114, even with an injured 18 in that. His elite combination of disposal efficiency (83%) and intercepts (8.5 per game) are the perfect pairing for SuperCoach scores. Despite the attention that comes most weeks and the fact he's over 30, he'll be a top six defender in 2024 again. There's some price upside given the injured score, however he's very expensive and I think I'll wait for a lower score and price drop before jumping on. Update: talk of midfield, which is a shock, but then again he attended 15% CBAs in the L5 of 2023. The way he gets fed in defence and how many intercepts he gets (8.5 per game), I actually think he'll be better in defence, but it's something to watch in the pre-season.
Short: Another top six season, despite a 18 in Round 1, he's just a SuperCoach star

Comment: After back-to-back 120+ seasons, regressed in 2023, reducing his average by 23 to 98. It started with hamstring tightness in the pre-season and then tore his meniscus in Round 6, seeing him miss the next 10 weeks. On return, he played a less prominent role, averaging 59% CBAs compared to the 80% he averaged in the prior two seasons. It appeared the Suns were looking at the future and the likes of Sam Flanders and Humphrey getting a run in the middle. It was probably the right call given Miller is now 28 and unlikely to be in their starting midfield when they push for a premiership. With a new coach, it's hard to know what role Miller will play in 2024. If he got back to a 75%+ CBA mid, he's the perfect underpriced premium that we can build our starting squad with. If not, he might struggle in a new system that will likely yield less SuperCoach points, especially with Flanders, Anderson and Rowell all getting more of the ball. With a Round 3 bye, it might pay to use the first two rounds to assess the role before jumping on.
Short: Pushed out of the midfield on return from injury, can certainly bounce back if Hardwick has him in his midfield sights but that's not guaranteed

Comment: After finishing 2021 as a top two ruck and one of the best scorers in SuperCoach, Darcy has been disappointing since. Nothing went right in 2022, a broken thumb, sore groins and then an Achilles injury that kept him out of the first practice match and Round 1. The recruitment of Luke Jackson quelled any chance of a bounce back in 2023, however he still managed to average 111 after he returned from injury mid-season. I still think it's crazy that he's younger than Tim English and given he's heading into his age 25 season, he should be at his peak as English was last year. However, the top two rucks of the past have largely been solo rucks who take more than 80% of the contests. With Jackson there, that's unlikely to happen. And surprise, he's had another interrupted pre-season, so we might see another slow start.
Short: Primed at 25, unfortunately for him he's not the solo ruck and he's had another interrupted pre-season, otherwise he could challenge the top 2

Comment: I've always been bullish on Will Day's prospects, but even I didn't believe the experiment of the skinny, injury prone defender as in inside mid would work. And boy was I wrong. Day excelled in his first season as a midfielder, improving his average by 32 points per game and winning the Hawks' B&F. More impressively, he was more impactful IRL than his SuperCoach scores suggested. He displayed a great balance of inside ball winning ability and tackles with outside run and marks. He will no doubt improve again with another pre-season under his belt. At his price, he'll need to be a keeper and I doubt we'll see him improve that much, but he'll certainly be one for the future. Update: pre-season foot injury might see him miss the start of the season. Bumped him down a bit.
Short: What a breakout as an inside mid and going to be a star of the future, pre-season foot injury will slow his start
AA season on the wing, but only averaged 93 which shows how hard it is to score as a mid without CBAs

Comment: Whitfield finally returned to defence under Kingsley and finally looked himself again. He took a while to warm up, but averaged 107 post-bye and 108 in finals. It shouldn't be a surprise, given he's averaged 105 twice before. He did have a mortgage on the distribution back then, whereas now he's competing with Himmelberg, Ash and Cumming. But at 29, I can see him remaining a 102+. That would be enough to knock on the door of the top six defenders, and underpriced at 93. I'm just not sure I'm ready to be burnt again.
Short: 107 post-bye now back in his natural position and that would be enough to knock on the door of the top six defenders

Comment: After bursting onto the scene and looking like a top level Fantasy mid for the future decade, averaging 87, 101 and 1117 in his first three seasons, Walsh has been underwhelming in the last two. There have been a few factors for the regression. A pre-season syndesmosis injury in 20222 and off-season back surgery in 2023. The worrying part was that it was his back-half of 2023, when he should've been at full fitness and peaking in CBAs at 59%, yet only averaged 101. He won enough of the ball (averaged 28.5 disposals, more than the top eight mids), he just had a low kick-to-handball ratio (0.76 v 1.2 of the top 8) and lacked counting stats of marks and tackles. However, this turned in the finals where he increased his CBAs to 68%, the same level where he averaged 117 in 2021, and averaged 122, winning the Garry Ayres medal for the best player in the finals. Priced at 103, there is no question he's underpriced - he nearly averaged that in his second season. A full pre-season for the first time in three years will do wonders. The question is if he can maintain the 115+ level which he needs to at that price. The early bye (Round 2) hurts, but I think he can challenge for a starting spot regardless.
Short: Injury interrupted pre-seasons twice in a row has seen a regression, but if the finals were any indication, we're about to remember how good Walsh is in 2024

Comment: Of all the breakouts in 2023, Briggs was probably the most impressive. From a 3rd choice ruck at GWS to All-Australian calculations, an amazing rise from the 24-year-old. He averaged the 3rd most tackles amongst rucks (behind Nank and Marshall) and less than two HO to advantage than the top 2. That means his scoring is sustainable, as we saw throughout 2023 when we (I) was waiting for him to come back to earth. At 24, he's only going to improve. However, I doubt it will be by enough to contend with English, Marshall, Gawn or Grundy, so as he's the 5th most expensive ruck, I don't think he'll better that on averages in 2023.
Short: Skyrocketed to be a top five ruck and could stay there for the next five years

Comment: The mid-season draft sensation took his game to another level in 2023. He stepped up in the absence of Mitchell and O'Meara but he actually didn't get the initial CBA bump I expected, going from 66% in 2022 with Titch and JOM in the side to 69% in pre-bye in 2023. This stepped up to 75% in the last five games, and his scoring reflected the boost, averaging 119 in that time. That would rank him as a top 10 mid, something we wouldn't have expected a year ago. He has the tools to do so, with disposals, efficiency, contested rate and marks all in-line with the top eight mids. Where he lacked was tackles (4.3 v 5.9), which is a shock given he set the AFL record for tackles on debut with 14. One to watch in the pre-season, and Day out will only boost.
Short: 119 in L5 with the boost in CBAs, if he remains at 75% plus he could go to another level again

Comment: Now this kid can seriously play. He improved his output again in 2023, however, his season felt a bit underwhelming. He followed up his 3rd season where he attended 79% CBAs in his last five to just 38% in his L5 of 2023. He's one of those players who are more damaging in real-life than in SuperCoach, showcased by his 16 Brownlow votes last season, the only Swan to receive more than 10, after 12 votes in 2022. That's a lot of votes for someone who averaged less than 100 in that time. Heading into his 5th season, he'll no doubt improve again with fitness and natural progression. But with the Swans recruiting Taylor Adams and James Jordon for midfield roles, I'm not sure he'll get the role required to challenge the top eight mids, especially considering the opposition attention he receives, such is the damaging nature of his game.
Short: Heading into his 5th season, the future AFL star should improve again, but he's one of those players who are better IRL than SuperCoach

Comment: Houston has been a mainstay in Port's defence for a few years now, but started to get the recognition he deserves in 2023. He's always shown a high ceiling, scoring over 120 five times in 2022, but it was the consistency that took him from a mid-to-high 90s defender to a top 6. He averaged 113 post-bye and 122 in the finals. The Power make an effort to get the ball in his hands given how good of a kick he is, which is exactly what you want as a SuperCoach defender. On that form, he'll be a top six defender again in 2024 and based on his finish to last season, he could even go higher.
Short: Arrived as a top six defender in 2023 and his form post-bye and in finals suggests he'll remain there in 2024

Comment: After experimenting as a midfielder/forward for 12 months, Short returned to his natural position of a running defender post-bye in 2023. However, even at his best, he never averaged over 100, which was similar to his output post-bye. He'll be around the mark, but lacks the intercept and contested game to elevate himself into the top six territory.
Short: Back in defence but lacks the intercept and contested game to elevate himself into the top six territory

Comment: Gawn has been on a steady SuperCoach decline since averaging 140 in 2020, dropping 19 points in 2021, six points in 2022 and a further eight points in 2023. The last two seasons has largely been on the back of sharing the ruck duties, with Luke Jackson in 2022 and then unbelievably with Grundy last year. His CBAs reduced from 93% in 2020 to 46%(!) pre-bye in 2023. Not surprisingly, the Gawn/Grundy combo didn't work and the Dees left Grundy out of the side for much of the second half of the season and all of finals. Again, not surprisingly, we say Gawn returned to be one of the best rucks in the comp, IRL and Fantasy. His season high of 162 came from 91% CBAs. In his six games over 120, he averaged 75% CBAs. In his seven scores under 90, he averaged 59% CBAs. Grundy is now gone and Max is back solo. At 32, we won't see him hit the heights of 2020, or possibly even 2021. However, I still have him as a top two ruck for 2024. The early bye isn't ideal, but he does have until Round 6 for his first bye, and he's got too many points and cash to have to wait until then.
Short: His six scores over 120 last season he averaged 75% CBAs, no Grundy, bring it on

Comment: It's been a rocky ride for Rowell after bursting on the scene to average 127 in his first four career games after averaging 124 at under 19 level. He's since battled injuries (shoulder, knee) and form, but finally showed his talent in 2023, leading the league in tackles, pressure acts and second in clearances. Unfortunately, this didn't result in decent SuperCoach scoring. He plays completely inside with zero spread to get easy possession, highlighted by his 65% contested rate (top eight mids 46%) incredibly low 1.9 marks per game (top eight mids 4.3). He looked purely focused on his role which at times meant manning an opposition mid and winning the footy came second. Unless we see a distinct change in his ball hunting and spread, I think he'll remain around the 100-110 mark, and fall short of the 110+ mark required to be a good selection.
Short: Despite leading the comp in tackles, pressure acts and second in clearances, only 1.9 marks per game is going to make it hard for him to put up any score of note
+22 points last season as the big bodied mid, but Essendon might need some more spark in there for 2024

Comment: Macrae was the most prolific SuperCoach scorer from 2018 to 2021. However, you wouldn't think that after watching him in 2022 and 2023. Even in his good seasons, when he doesn't get the inside role he wants, he looks a shadow of himself. Unfortunately, it was this way for the majority of 2023 - just 36% CBAs after being a 75%+ guy for years. I expected Dunkley would open up an obvious spot in the midfield. However, the Dogs' preferred midfield mix was Libba, Bont and Treloar, with all three averaging over 78% CBAs. It's a very tight midfield rotation. There were multiple games where Bevo used Caleb Daniel over Macrae. From the outside, it appears that the Dogs wanted more pace in there and didn't want to sacrifice Bont or Libba, both of whom had terrific seasons. With forward status, his history and the fact he's not even 30, he has to be on your watchlist for 2024. However, I have the feeling we'll see much the same in terms of role for Macrae and we all know what that means. But in a weak forward pool, it will still be enough to be a top forward. Update: Smith out for the year should only help his cause. Although it sounds like Sanders has stepped right into an inside mid spot. I'll still need to see his role in the pre-season. Update: A pre-season hamstring injury is not ideal but my mind will still be made up if/when we see his role in the pre-season games.
Short: 36% CBAs in 2023 as Dogs wanted to inject pace in there, pre-season games will determine if the most prolific SuperCoach scorer from 2018 to 2021 will bounce back or not

Comment: Tom Mitchell was a SuperCoach pig, averaging 129 in 2018 before missing the entire 2019 season with a broken leg. Since then, he hasn't reached those heights. You could put it down to the recovery, then being in a team that fast-track a rebuild and experimented with younger players through the midfield. A change of clubs gave me optimism that we might see the return of the Pig. However, I underestimated how 'team-first' they are at the Pies and Mitchell bought into that mentality. He averaged 95, less than he did when pushed out of the midfield at the Hawks. He had a great finals series, averaging 115. There might be a slight bump in CBAs with Adams leaving, but I think the Pies will begin to give more opportunity to youngsters Nick Daicos, Finlay Macrae and Ed Allen. Sadly, I think the big scoring days are over.
Short: The former SuperCoach stud is now a role player at the Pies and their 'team-first' mantra means his pig days are over
Brilliant season on the wing, but 93 is about as good as you'll get from that position

Comment: The risk with Duncan is that he's now over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries in the past. We know Geelong aren't afraid to rest players, even if named. So you'll have nervous moments with him in 2024. For that reason, Id prefer to start with safer options in defence, despite knowing he has the ability to be a top 10 defender.
Short: Over 30 and had his share of soft tissue injuries means I'm passing, despite his favourable SuperCoach game

Comment: I might have a new favourite player in the comp. The former Pick 11, who was described as the best kick at St Kilda from the moment he was drafted, showed he was just that in 2023 in a breakout second season. The Saints try to get the ball in his hands at any opportunity, as they should. However, the SuperCoach scoring system doesn't really reward those who get handed the ball. His 24% contested possession rate, nine lower than the Top six defenders at 33%, is why he averaged 85 in SuperCoach and 91 in AFL Fantasy. Combined with lower intercepts, tackles and disposals, it's going to make it hard for NWM to challenge the top six in SuperCoach until he starts winning more of his own ball. That will take time given he's still a developing 21-year-old, but I have a feeling we might see him amongst the top six defenders in the coming years.
Short: A second year breakout and 92 post-bye an indication of what we'll see for the next 10 years

Comment: Witts backed up his career high 2023 season of 110 with his second best average of 106 in 2023. His scoring is always favoured by a league high hitout to advantage rate, which is incredibly important for SuperCoach given normal hitouts aren't worth anything and sharked hitouts net negative points. At the half way point of the season, it looked as though he was going to be a top two ruck for the second straight year, as he averaged an incredible 115. However, he slowed post-bye, as he did in 2022, to average 98 on the way home. At 31, it's hard to see him improving and with Gawn and Grundy now solo, it's hard to see him being amongst the top three rucks again in 2024.
Short: Aided by a league high HTA rate but unlikely to improve compared to some of the other rucks in 2024

Comment: Dusty had a sneaky good season in 2023. The 32-year-old star hasn't been a SuperCoach relevant player for three seasons now after being one of the best in the years before that. However, he wound by the clock in 2023 to average 118 post-bye, including 122 in his last 5. With so many players losing forward status in 2024, he comes in as the 4th best forward and all of a sudden becomes relevant again. The fact he's now 32 and hasn't averaged over 94 in three seasons, it's hard to pay a price-tag of 94 knowing it's unlikely he'll improve it. So despite being in my starting 'Best 22', I don't think he makes a good starting selection.
Short: Back relevant with the lack of forwards but 32 and hasn't averaged over 94 in three seasons makes it hard to pick with confidence, said to be spending more time in the middle though

Comment: Daniel felt every bit of 'Bevo' in 2023, as he was used as a defender, mid and even forward across the season. Of all the positions, he does his best from a SuperCoach point of view playing as a half-back. However, the fact he comes into 2024 with MID/FWD status shows how little he was used there. Dale is now the main man back there and Ed Richards was used as his 2IC. That left Daniel in no-mans-land and I have no idea how he will be used in 2024. With the lack of forward options, he has to be on the radar over the pre-season, given his career best average would rank him as the F1 for 2024. But that would require him to move back to defence and there's no certainty of that happening.
Short: The gun defender of the past comes in with MID/FWD status which tells you everything you need to know about Bevo

Comment: 2023 saw Parker dip below 100 for the first time in six years. His average doesn't reflect it, but he actually had another very good season in 2023. He's had forward status in the past and following the recruitment of Taylor Adams and James Jordon, plus the fact he's now over 30, means we might see him spend more time out of the middle and possibly gain DPP during the season. Until then, he's unlikely to make an impact as a MID-only in SuperCoach.
Short: Will need forward status to be relevant in 2023, but there's a decent chance of that happening

Comment: A premier defender in SuperCoach from 2019 to 2021, Lloyd has slowly reduced his scoring in the last few seasons. Once the Swans' primary distributor, he's now handed over those duties to Nick Blakey. He's still a consistent defender, and removing the injured 31 in 2023, he would have averaged 99. However, it's just hard to see him ever reaching the 107+ heights of the past and I'd rather target someone with more upside.
Short: Now six seasons in a row of 92+, but at 30 he's becoming more of a role player

Comment: Came into 2023 discounted and disappointed. In a football sense, he had the lowest contested possession rate of any mid with over 35% CBAs and also averaged just three tackles per game, compared to the top eight mids of 6.5. I personally think West Coast's inside brigade should be Tim Kelly, Yeo + the kids (Ginbey, Hewett, Reid) and see less of Sheed and Gaff on the inside. A foot injury in the pre-season might make that decision for them.
Short: A foot injury in the pre-season and new recruits will likely see him pushed out of the middle

Comment: Flanders is the type of player these stats are made for. After some buzz in the 2023 pre-season, the former Pick 11 was in and out of the side in the first half of the season, averaging 44 from just 8% CBAs. In that time he was dominating the VFL, averaging 104 AFL Fantasy points. He finally got his chance once Stewy Dew left, and averaged 106 post-bye from 38% CBAs, increasing to 43% in the L5. He enters 2024 priced at 88 and with forward status, thanks to his first half of the season in the graveyard shift. The only flag is the new coach, so his role isn't confirmed, and the early bye (Round 3).  It might be hard saying no if he goes 110+ in Round 0, but I think I'll stay strong and wait until after his bye.
Short: Got his chance in the back end and delivered, 106 from 38% CBAs post-bye, if role sticks with new coach he will be top 6

Comment: I had been waiting to see what McCluggage would produce SuperCoach wise once moved inside from his customary wing role, given he played inside when he was in juniors and averaged more Fantasy points than Tim Taranto. He made the move in 2022, however he didn't get the boost I was hoping for, lagging the elite mids in disposal efficiency, contested possession rate, tackles and clearances. He did get better as the year went on, averaging 104 post-bye. He lacks the inside game of the top level mids in SuperCoach and that will likely leave him a level below again.
Short: 104 post-bye which is closer to where he's been the last three seasons, still a level below the top ones who have a stronger inside game

Comment: This time last year, we were debating who out of Young or Daicos will push into the top 6. After a few rounds, there was a clear answer. The former number seven pick didn't make the jump we expected of him, following his 94 average in 2022. Luke Ryan remained the primary distributor for Freo, despite Young's elite kicking skills. However, a move to the midfield at the end of the season was a turning point. Young averaged 58% CBAs in his L5, playing a defensive role as a big bodied mid. Freo have been crying out for a play of that nature and he passed all the eye tests to suggest he could be the man. He averaged 107 in this time, which as a defender and priced at 94, would make him a great selection. And you'd hope he can better that with a full pre-season training as a midfielder, which he is. I'm on board.
Short: A move to the middle late in the year where he averaged 107 in L5 is an indication of whats to come

Comment: Greene has the potential to be a top six forward if unleashed, as he's shown in the past, he can be a prolific ball winner when playing in the midfield. However, he's one of the more dangerous forwards in the comp and as such has settled in that role. He can still push the 90-mark in such role, but unless we see an unlikely role change, there not enough upside to consider in Classic.
Short: Settled in the forward role where he impressively can push the 90 mark but not the 100s when he's played midfield in the past

Comment: After winning the Brownlow in 2022, and averaging 111 for the season (115 excluding his injured game), Cripps was knocking on the door of the premium mids. However, he returned to an 98 average in 2023, and unlike his underwhelming scoring seasons of 2021 and 2020, he wasn't hampered by injury. It appeared that Carlton made a switch to move the ball quicker, which led to less possessions for their mids. Cripps' impact was still as strong as ever, he just didn't have the consistently high SuperCoach scoring games that he did in 2022. It worked, with Carlton storming home and making a prelim. I imagine Carlton adopting a similar method in 2024 and that means Cripps will score more like his 2023 season, than his 2022. Therefore he's not the value that he appears to be based on his discount to career high average.
Short: Is a top-line SuperCoacher when at his best, including his Brownlow winning 2022, but been a 90s guy for three of the last four which makes the bounce back to 110+ unlikely

Comment: The Crows just don't rely on O'Brien as much and certainly don't use him around the ground as they once did. He'll likely be a mid-90s ruckman again, but there's not much upside there.
Short: He'll likely be a mid-90s ruckman again and even less if they hand over the reins to Thilthorpe and it will be even lower

Comment: Moore was introduced into the midfield rotation in 2022 and averaged 100 post-bye from 42% CBAs. He was brilliant there and there was hope that this would be a sign of things to come. However, he returned to his customary forward role in 2023, attending just 2% CBAs for the season. He scores great considering the role, averaging 91 for the season, the same as he was averaging in 2022 before the role change. With so many young mids rotating in the midfield at the Hawks, Moore is likely to stay as a forward for now. But he should always be on the radar as we know he can average 100+ if the CBAs come.
Short: Back to the forward-line after 100 from 42% CBAs post-byes in 2022, still can score but we'll need a role change for him to be a top six lock in 2024

Comment: After 13 seasons in a row averaging at least 100, Pendlebury has now gone below that level three years in a row, While still great IRL, he's finally slowing down from a SuperCoach perspective. He still plays a prominent role in the Pies' midfield, attending 66% of their centre bounces. At 36, I'm waiting for him to step back and possibly get DPP at some stage during the season, but he keeps getting it done.
Short: 3 years in a row sub-100 shows he's finally slowing down
Outstanding season but wingmen are capped to the 90 mark in SuperCoach so this is the best he'll be
Great season IRL and displayed a SuperCoach game (+11), but role is still too defensive for me to consider
Back-to-back Colemans, but the fact he's only averaged 90 in that time shows the game isn't suited to key forwards

Comment: De Goey burst into SuperCoach relevance in 2021 when he was shifted into the midfield and averaged 110 for the second half of the season. McRae has played him as a pure mid the last two seasons, however never met those scoring heights, averaging 93 in that time. It been a mixture of both the Pies' low possession game style and the focus for De Goey to get his possessions in a dangerous position forward of centre. It's working IRL, where he's a genuine star of the comp, so I doubt we'll see the 110+ De Goey again under McRae.
Short: Now a genuine midfielder, however McRae's low possession game plan and focus to get the ball forward of centre means he might not be that 110+ player again

Comment: After back-to-back 92+ seasons playing on a wing at Port, Amon averaged 81 for the Hawks in a similar role pre-bye in 2023. He played more in defence at the end of 2023, averaging an impressive 96 post-bye from 20% kick-ins and 109 in L5 from 30%. Unfortunately, he didn't play there enough to get defender status which I think would've made him a genuine starting options. It's also likely that the Hawks move the ball quicker with a more competitive side, meaning less marking opportunities for their defenders who took a huge number of marks last season. I never like picking players in the hope of DPP and there is a chance he goes back to a wing role in 2024, so I'm out.
Short: Scoring had always been capped due to wing role, but move to defence to finish 2023 with a big spike in scoring gives him a chance to surpass that

Comment: Bolton is a genuine star of the comp IRL. However, he's yet to match those SuperCoach figures given the high impact nature of his game. A new coach might want him to spend more time in the middle in 2024, as he complements Taranto, Hopper and Prestia well as he adds a bit of spark, but that's purely speculative. An early bye rules him out regardless, but at least we'll know his role and scoring potential once the bye occurs and upgrade season begins.
Short: Star IRL, will we see more mid time for him to become a star SuperCoach player?

Comment: Worpel bounced back after two poor seasons in a row. After averaging 97 in just his 2nd season, he dropped in average every season since before bottoming out with a 56 in 2022. With all the young mids at the Hawks (Ward, MacDonald, Newcombe, Day, Mackenzie, Nash, even more Moore), I thought we wouldn't see him much again. However, he managed 67% CBAs in 2023 to average a respectable 90. I personally think Ward (23%) and Mackenzie (20%) should get more opportunity for their development and it shouldn't come from Day, Nash or Newcomb. Regardless, his poor kicking efficiency caps his scoring, and won't be SuperCoach relevant this season.
Short: Nice bounce back but more opportunity should be given to the kids

Comment: Redman backed up his breakout 93 in 2022 with 91 in 2023. He's displayed a nice ceiling over that time, with 7 x 120+ scores. However, with Ridley and McGrath also taking distribution duties, Redman is also prone to a low score (11 sub-70 scores in the last two seasons). It's going to be hard for him to challenge the top six unless he becomes the clear number one man back there, which I doubt will happen.
Short: Back-to-back 90+ seasons but didn't come on as a top six prospect as I expected and Martin set to be the main distributor may hurt his output

Comment: Scott had a terrific season, but still just managed an average of 76. He played a pure wing-role, which means a low contested rate (23%) and tackles (2.6). That's never good for SuperCoach scoring He's now lost his defender status, so a MID-only who doesn't get CBAs is never a good sign, but he certainly has some scoring talent. With the retirements of Ziebell and Hall, Sheezel moving into the middle and the interrupted pre-season of Fisher, we might see Scott roam across half-back and feast as he did at the backend of 2023. As with Amon, I don't like picking midfielders who don't get CBAs in the hope they get DPP, so I think he's one I'd wait on to see the role and scoring. But he can certainly outscore that price in the right environment. 10 Feb Update: Low-grade calf strain in the preseason.
Short: Nice winger, but wingers aren't what you want in SuperCoach

Comment: Brayshaw returned to a prominent the midfield in 2023 when Oliver was out post-bye, averaging 66% CBAs. The scoring wasn't as high as it has been in the past in that role, but he still managed to average 98 in that time. Oliver should be back in there but Harmes (27% CBAs) and Jordon (27% CBAs) are both gone, so I think he'll remain a regular midfielder in 2024. That would put him underpriced, but the fact he's still yet to average over 100 in his nine year career, I doubt he'll suddenly become at top six defender.
Short: Got the bump with Oliver out but with no Harmes or Jordon, I think he'll remain in the middle

Comment: Dale has been a revolution since his move to defence, clearly putting up his best three SuperCoach seasons. He takes the kick-in responsibilities (56%) which helped him score points and his solid ball use (78% efficiency) is a key feature of his game. He was averaging 106 in the first half of 2022, however he's typically been around the 90 mark in his splits. I think you'd need more from someone at this price point as a starting squad selection.
Short: Kick-in responsibilities (53%) and solid ball use (78% efficiency) are key features of his game, however 13 scores less than 90 make me doubt he can make it as a top six defender

Comment: The mature aged SSP of 2022 backed up his impressive debut season with one that had him in All-Australian discussions in 2023. He had a stretch from Round 10 to 15 where he averaged 128, bucking the trend of the low wing scores. He had six scores over 120, again impressive for a wing, but was also prone to a low one with seven scores under 70, such is the nature of the position. However, an off-season switch to the half-back role, with the Bombers making it clear they want to get the ball in his hands and for him to be the major distributor down back. This is only good news for his SuperCoach prospects and he might have an impact once he gets defender DPP, but as per Amon and Scott, I'd rather wait until they have the confirmed stats and pick CBA mids in my midfield.
Short: Had a hot patch in the middle of the year to show he can score and now said to be the distributor off half-back, a role that should yield more points than the wing

Comment: Zorko has been a SuperCoach stalwart throughout his career. His scoring is boosted by above average kick-to-handball ratio, marks, goals and tackles. With all this combined, he's a unique player who doesn't require 30 touches to get a decent SuperCoach score. However, he's now 34 and coming off a number of injuries in the last few years, so despite the thin forward-line and his strong scoring potential, you just couldn't go there.
Short: 4 games with less than 50% TOG in the last two seasons, has and can be a stud but the body lets him down too often now

Comment: Despite being very young in ruck terms, Jackson has the attributes to be a top-line SuperCoach ruck. And with forward status, he could be the number one forward. In his first season at Freo, he surpassed 100 11 times, and averaged 60% CBAs in those 11, including a monster 173 when he had 88%. However, he had eight sub-90 games, and averaged 28% CBAs in those eight. Freo just signed Sean Darcy, who is also a very good ruck. In the 15 games with Darcy, Jackson averaged 87. He's got attributes that I think he can be a decent scorer even with Darcy in the team, but he's going to have to take the number one mantle for him to be the 100+ forward we're crying out for this season.
Short: Averaged 87 with Darcy and 118 without

Comment: Guthrie was a low-key gun SuperCoacher in 2021, averaging 109. He hasn't reached those heights since and battled with injury last season. Word is he's back to full fitness and while he's priced well below what he's capable of, he's now 31 playing for a team who notoriously rest their players, particularly those over 30. I can't trust that the minutes and matches are always going to be there, despite his discounted price.
Short: Comes in discounted and his best is good enough, but we haven't seen that for a while and now that he's 31, I doubt we see it again

Comment: Not many half-back flankers are taken as a top four pick, so Ash obviously has the talent. After an odd shift by Leon Cameron, where he played in the midfield, at times as a tagger, he finally moved back to his natural position under Kingsley. He had a very good season, but with Whitfield and Himmelberg also back there, there are a few mouths to feed for distribution. He'll be a 100+ defender in time, but I think 2024 will be too soon.
Short: He'll be a 100+ defender in time, but I think 2024 will be too soon

Comment: No easy way to put it, Mills had a shocker in 2023. After back-to-back 112+ seasons, nothing went right in 2023 and he dropped his average by a massive 28 points per game. It started with him forced to play a key defensive role after many of the Swans' key backs went down. His defensive attributes and versatility has always been a burden for him in SuperCoach, often shifted to be loose man in defence or to a wing and play behind the ball. But never key defence. He averaged 12% CBAs from Round 4-6, including 0% in Round 5. He didn't score over 100 in this time. Swans then got some players back and Mills started building in the midfield, with 47% then 63% CBAs in Round 7 and 8. However, he popped a calf in the first minute of Round 9 when on 4. He returned in Round 15 when Swans beat WC by 171 and was subbed off just after half time. So all these scenarios have been built into his price for 2024, which is at an average of 88. He showed he still had it when he scored 143 in the final round of the season. However, there were still seven sub-100 scores 10, including a 38(!) in Round 23, despite being back to fitness. And to top it off, he injured himself on Mad Monday and will miss the start of the season.
Short: Nothing went right in 2024 and to top it off, he injured himself on Mad Monday and will miss the start of the season - stash for draft with potential defender status coming

Comment: 2023 was Cameron's first full season as the number one ruck and expectations were high after he averaged 97 to finish 2022 after Grundy got injured. He started hot, averaging 120 in his first 2, before injuring his MCL in Round 3 before 3/4 time when on 89. He missed the next six weeks, before being eased back in, starting as the sub in Round 10 (64% TOG) and 75% TOG in Round 11, averaging just 71. He then averaged 101 in his next 3, including a game rucking against the Gawn/Grundy combo and looked to be a top six forward candidate for the run home. However, Cameron missed a week for injury and Mason Cox started to take more of the centre-bounce ruck contests, and had a great impact. So much so that Cox was the Pie's number one ruck throughout the finals series, leaving Cameron to attend 33% of the centre bounces during the finals. With McStay out for the season and Cox's influence late in the year, there's a chance we see Cameron spend more time forward in 2024 and now that he's lost his forward status, he doesn't present as a great starting option in Fantasy.
Short: Spent more time forward late in the season with Cox being the main man and we might see more of that in 2024 with McStay down
Terrible news with Smith out for the year with an ACL
The man can score (above 110 PP100% TOG the L5 seasons, 120 VFL avg '23) but Dunkley coming in massively hurt his spot in the side, couldn't get away from the sub vest and doubt that will change
Scores better than the average key forward, and averaged 98 pre-bye in 2023 which would make him a clear top 6, but it's too hard for a key forward to sustain that level for a full season

Comment: Once a high-scoring defender, Crisp has became a full-time midfielder since McRae arrived and his scoring has taken a hit as a result. He's well under-priced what's he's capable of, but as a midfield only option who has averaged sub-90 in the last 18 months, I can't have him.
Short: Averaged sub-90 since moving from defence, unless we see an unlikely role change, he's not going to be relevant in 2024
Shattering knee injury late 2023 and will miss most of 2024, showed enough to suggest he'll be a star in the future
Averaged around the 90-mark since being the number one ruck, that's a level below the top ones

Comment: The highly rated 24-year-old has had his fair share of injuries in the last few seasons. A beautiful kick and found his spot on a half-back flank and displayed some great signs, including three scores over 120. It's consistency that Powell hasn't had to date, but under Hardwick who was noted for having high scoring half-backs (Houli, Short), Powell should have a career season in 2024. The early bye (Round 3) rules out any chance of starting with him, but I'm quietly confident we'll see him push his average towards the 100 mark in 2024.
Short: Yet to have a full run of it, but showed flashes of brilliance (IRL and SC), so if he can improve his consistency under Harwick, he could be a sneaky option
The Irishman was second to Newcombe for CBAs in 2023 and showed great improvement, but I doubt we'll see him improve to be a relevant MID-only option

Comment: After a prolific junior career and earning his stripes in defence once drafted, McGrath moved to the midfield in 2020. He looked good initially, but had back-to-back 80 seasons and reducing CBAs as he mixed his time between midfield, wing and half-back. Brad Scott committed to settling McGrath on a half-back flank, however, it didn't result in much change to his scoring, with another mid-80 season. There's too much competition for distribution at the Dons, with Redman, Ridley and Hind taking a lot of kicks and now add in Nic Martin, so unless something changes, I dont think well see McGrath breakout to be a top six defender.
Short: A move to defence for the former number one pick didn't result in any improvement in scoring and now has Martin to compete with
Been a solid 80s-guy since moving to defence, as have many of his defensive teammates and out of all of them, he's the least likely to push that to the 100+ needed

Comment: Blicavs is such a unique player who has played pretty much every position on the ground. However, the upside isn't there unless hes unleashed as a full time ruck, which I doubt will happen.
Short: The mid/ruck combo shows how unique he is, but unless he becomes the Cats' number one ruck option, he won't score enough to be worthy

Comment: Smith has been a consistent defender for a number of years now without taking that next step and being a Fantasy relevant one. He always played second fiddle to Laird and then Dawson, but last year both played in the midfield, however he didn't manage to get a boost in scoring. His kick-ins are low for someone with such a nice kick (only 25%) and only reduced as the season went on. He's shown the 80-mark is his max.
Short: Had been behind Laird then Dawson for distribution, but with neither there in 2023, he didn't manage to boost his score enough
Undergoing his second knee recon

Comment: Matt Crouch has struggled with groin issues, a broken leg and form the last three seasons after being a multiple 110+ mid previously. Despite putting up big numbers in the reserves, it appeared the Crows had moved on from Crouch. However, he returned to the team in Round 16 and played the rest of the season. He averaged 6.4 clearances a game and many thought he played career best football - as previously he has been criticised for being just an accumulator and getting cheap footy. He averaged 108 SuperCoach points in that time and 112 in his L5 - which shows those people might have a point. I was shocked to see he's still only 28, so there's no reason why the Crows should be moving past him if he continues to play the inside role he did last year. However, his spot in the 23 is still going to be under pressure, so it's a high price to pay for someone who could get dropped on any given week. 10 Feb Update: Sounds like he's a first choice midfielder, I've bumped him up a bit and getting pretty keen.
Short: Former stud got back in the team and form to finish 2023, but spot in 23 is always going to be under pressure

Comment: Vlastuin had a career best Fantasy year in 2022 on the back of Houli retiring and Short moving into the midfield. However, Vlastuin gave up Richmond's primary distributor in 2023 as Short returned to defence and Rioli broke-out. Yze has flagged positional changes, but I doubt we see anything for Vlastuin to become a top six defender.
Short: Short returning to defence and Rioli breaking out saw Vlastuin drop back nine points after a career best 2022
Couldn't get back into the side after Round 7 and Young moving in the midfield will only make it harder, best on in the intra-club is promising signs though
Bounced back in 2023 but still yet to replicate his 2021 form when Sicily was out

Comment: Noble had been a regular in defence for the Pies after being picked up in the mid-season draft of 2019. However, he found himself out of the side to finish the season and at this price, you need someone with job security and more upside.
Short: Found himself out of the side after being a solid 70-80s defender

Comment: There was a bit of hope for Hopper leading into 2023, following a trade to the Tigers who lacked midfield depth. However, he wasn't great, averaging 79 points from 16 matches. He did have two injury impacted games and removing those he averaged 86, still well short of other midfielders with regular CBAs. However, he's had some consistent CBAs in the past, with 75% and 72% in 2020 and 2021 for averages of 96 and 91. For an inside mid, he actually wins less contested possessions than the top eight and at a lower disposal efficiency. He's certainly underpriced from what he can produce, however at that price, you need him to put up top eight numbers, Unless we see a bump in both those metrics, he's always going to be capped.
Short: Yet to average 100 in eight seasons, he has a capped SuperCoach game despite the CBA opportunities

Comment: Ridley has the attributes to be an elite SuperCoach defender with his safe ball use (92%), high kick-to-handball ratio, intercept marking and spoils. After a modest start to 2023, averaging 87 from the first seven matches, Ridley was concussed on 18 in Round 7. It appeared that snapped him into action, as he went on to average 120 in his next 6. That even included a game where he was subbed off again before 3/4 time. He managed 138 in Round 15 before getting injured again, this time missing the remainder of the season. He had genuine excuses in 2023, which included being forced to play deep defence when the Bombers had some injuries. If he can have a clean run of injuries and avoid the lockdown role, he can propel himself into the top six this season. The role is something I'll be watching in the pre-season and I've got my eye on him again to start 2024.
Short: Three games that were impacted by injury in 2023 held him back from being a genuine top six defender, Mackay arrival should help but with be offset by Martin taking some kick-ins
22% contested rate at 77% efficiency caps his SuperCoach scoring despite the favourable role
Evergreen forward scores above average for a key forward and for a 33-year-old, but not the ideal combo in this game, despite his high ceiling games

Comment: The move of Rioli to the half-back flank has been a revelation and he's fast becoming a star running defender of the comp. He even looked to be improving again on his 2022 season when he averaged 95 pre-bye. However, that regressed to 74 post-bye when Short returned from injury and to the backline. Yze has flagged positional changes, but I think there's no question he'll remain in the role, but with Short there also, he won't push that average to the 105+ mark needed to be a relevant defender this season.
Short: Was one of the better HBs in the comp to start 2023, but regressed when Short returned

Comment: Heeney has been the ultimate tease in SuperCoach. It feels like every year there is talk of 'more midfield time' for Heeney which never eventuates. In fact, he had his career high CBA season last year with 13%. It increased to 29% in the final where he played a defensive role of all things, but that didn't result in much to his score. With Adams and Jordon arriving, and the likely midfield boost for Warner, I doubt we'll see much change in 2024. He still manages to score pretty well for almost a pure forward, however there's no value in his price if he remains as a forward. So unless we see that 50% CBA number in the pre-season and want to go down that road again.
Short: The ultimate tease has almost run out of 'more midfield time' chances

Comment: Dangerfield has been on a steady decline since 2017 when he was the number one man in SuperCoach. He's now 33 and Geelong have always taken a cautious approach with their older players, indicated by his 18 games last season at just 65% TOG. That, combined with his MID-only status, makes him not an option this season, despite being priced 46 points below his career high.
Short: 2 sub-90 seasons in a row suggests the past SuperCoach-beast is well past it in this game now

Comment: Moved into the midfield post-bye in 2022 and in 2023 led the Cats' CBAs for non-rucks. However, he's averaged sub-90 in that time. His game is highlighted by his strong tackle pressure, but he doesn't hunt the ball enough and he's one of those who is too team orientated to make a impact in SuperCoach.
Short: Pressure midfielder who is too team orientated to make an impact in SuperCoach

Comment: The speedy half-back has now settled on a half-back flank at the Dogs and played consistently in 2023. However, he's second in line behind Dale for kick-ins and general distribution, which will cap his scoring below the 100 mark.
Short: Breakout season, but behind Dale for kick-ins and general distribution, which will cap his scoring below the 100 mark unless Bevo does something crazy with Dale as some training reports suggest

Comment: Rowbottom has always been highly rated at the Swans as a tough, high-tackling inside mid. However, Swans have plenty of those and despite his high tackle count (7.3 per game), he could only manage 56% CBAs. He doesn't do much when he's not in the middle either, displayed by his extremely low marks, 1.1 per game. With two inside mids in Adams and Jordon arriving, I doubt we'll see Rowbottom hit the 75%+ CBAs figure he'd need to tackle his way to a 100 average.
Short: I doubt we'll see Rowbottom hit the 75%+ CBAs figure he'd need to tackle his way to a 100+ average

Comment: The former top 10 pick has had an up and down career to date. He looked to be a future star of the comp in his 3rd season when he averaged 95 in second half and 110 in his last 5. With CBAs increasing in line, and low TOG, he ticked all the boxes for a breakout. However, he's played just the 22 games since with a mixture of form, injury and personal issues. In his 12 games last season, he still showed he can mix it with the best and boasts a very impressive stat profile. He averages a better disposal efficiency, contested rate and more goals than the average top eight mid. Impressively, he averaged 4.3 clearances a game in 2023, despite attending 57% CBAs and having less than 20 disposals a game. However, with North recruiting another gun mid with Pick two and Sheezel tipped to play more inside, it's unlikely we'll see him increase those CBAs to a level which would see him win enough possessions to compete with the top 8. One to watch though if he gets forward status as he could play a bit role given the lack of forward depth this season. Update - away from the club and we may not see him again.
Short: Has the attributes to be a SuperCoach gun, but hard to see him getting enough inside opportunity, despite how effective he is when he's in there

Comment: Hunter's 2020 average was always going to be a stretch, given it was a small sample size of 10 games of 16-minute quarters. But even ignoring 2020, Hunter was always a consistent 90-100 guy, finding space on his wing accumulating plenty of marks and kicks. So there was some hope a change of clubs could see him return to that form, however he averaged the exact same as he did in his last season at the Dogs. So I think he's now just a classic wing in SuperCoach, who are MID-only, no CBAs and fail to go make much of an impact. A nagging calf injury has him in doubt for the opening round.
Short: A new team and played well, but still went sub-80 for the 2nd season in a row and back in-line with other wingmen
