Comment: Sidebottom has been a Fantasy gun of the past, but now takes a much lesser role at the Pies, splitting his time between wing and half-forward and rarely seeing centre bounces (just 2% in 2023). As a MID-only in 2024, he's unlikely to make an impact if he remains in his outside role.
Short: Now a 33-year-old wingman and not in the role that once made him a SuperCoach gun
Gun pressure forward who I imagine will be much the same for the Pies as he was for Freo
Played all but one game in 2023 after being in and out the three prior, but didn't show the SuperCoach upside he displayed early in his career, could see a rise with no Hurn, but is he Best 22?

Comment: Wines has had back-to-back disappointing seasons, dropping 33 points per game from his Brownlow winning 2021. He's battled with injury (a heart issue in 2022 and off-season knee surgery last season), but the main cause of his demise has been the emergence of the young stars Butters and Rozee. Add in Horne-Francis and there's been a clear shift to the new young mids at Port, with Wines' CBAs dropping to 42% post-bye (was 74% in his Brownlow year). He's certainly cheap, but at that price he's still going to need to be close to a top 15 mid to be worthwhile selection. For that, his CBAs need to return to over 65%, which will rely on Willem Drew (also 50% in 2023) losing his role, and given he was just added to the leadership group, might be unlikely. A pre-season watch.
Short: No longer the main man with Butters and Rozee taking over but he's extremely cheap and not as old as his drop-off suggests

Comment: Salem has had a poor two seasons. He's had excuses. In 2022 he injured his knee in the first minutes of Round 1 on 5, forcing him to miss the next 10 games. In 2023, Salem has been placed on a modified training program in the pre-season due to a thyroid concern. An uninterrupted pre-season could see a bounce back in 2024. However, even when he was fit in the last 24 months, he hasn't been the main distributor. Steven May takes a crazy amount of the kick-ins, and Salem took just 7% of them post-bye last year. Also the fact that he didn't go over 100 once, he's a long way from a top six defender.
Short: 2 poor seasons in a row and has lost the distribution duties at the Dees

Comment: Keays has shown he can score in this game when in the right role. He averaged 103 in 2021 and backed it up with 114 in the first half of 2022, attending 80% of the centre bounces across that time. However, there was a clear role change mid-season and Keays has since spent more and more time forward, 55% in H2 2022, 34% in the L5 2022, 30% H1 2023, 20% H2 2023 and 6% L5. In his six games he scored over 100 in 2023, he averaged 49%, so there's no doubt he has the capability. The CBA trend isn't in his favour though, and with the Crows looking to inject some more speed in there, I think we'll see Keays spend maintain his forward role in 2024 and not be the top six forward who plays in the midfield that we're after.
Short: Steady decline in CBAs and scoring since mid-way through 2022 and now pretty well a permanent forward
The 32-year-old will likely take a back seat this season

Comment: Drew has become a regular in the Power midfield, playing 70 games in the last three seasons at over 50% CBAs. I feel like Wines will see more inside time this season and it will come from Drew's usage, however even if he stays in the prominent midfield role, he's a pure inside midfielder and lacks the spread and easy possessions to make him a relevant option in Fantasy.
Short: A regular in Port's midfield but plays a team-first role
Showed nice dash as a wing, but even the best wingers don't cut it in this game and Henry isn't that

Comment: Showed he was up to it last season, being one of West Coast's best as the number one ruck. He's always been spoken about as a future key forward and second ruck, and the off-season recruitment of Flynn means we'll likely see him step into this role in 2024 and cap his growth in SuperCoach.
Short: Was the main man in 2023 and capped out at 77, will find it tougher this year alongside Flynn
Had a career year in 2023 as a mature body in a young struggling team, it's hard to see him topping that effort

Comment: I've like what I've seen from Hobbs in his first two seasons. He has slowly been introduced into the midfield, 15% CBAs in his debut season and 35% in 2023, increasing as the season goes on. He's got a hardnosed style that I think will benefit the Bombers going forward. There is a bit of a logjam of mids at the Dons. He ranked 6th for CBAs last season, behind Parish, Merrett, Setterfield and Shield. I think he'll leapfrog Shield and Setterfield, and along with Caldwell, be one of the first choice mids in 2024. Unfortunately, he lost his forward status, despite spending a lot of time forward. He would've been a perfect punt if he was available as a forward, however he's too risky as a MID-only option. 10 Feb Update: Minor AC joint injury will see him on modified duties for a week or two, but nothing serious.
Short: Will hope to spend more time in the middle where he showed enough to suggest he'll be a player of the future
Fringe wingman who is MID-only, not a SuperCoach option
94 in L5 when Young moved into the middle might be a sign of things to come

Comment: The man who has averaged 110+ twice in his career has significantly dropped in output the past three seasons. He battled with hamstring and knee issues in 2021 and a groin issue in 2022, which finally gave way with a complete rupture of his adductor in the final. This delayed his pre-season in 2023, however it was more the role change that hurt his scoring, dropping to just 39% CBAs and used as a pressure forward the most of the season. This led to a trade request to the Swans for supposedly more midfield time. The Swans certainly aren't short midfielders, however they do love a tough inside mid and Adams is every bit of that. In a season with a lack of forward options, Adams is exactly what we're looking for - underpriced, top six potential and potential for a bump in midfield time. The issue is the early bye in Round 5, but I'm prepared to start players with an early bye if they are value, which Adams is. We'll get a proper look at his role in Round 0, and I imagine most of the comp will be on board when they see him right amongst it then.
Short: In a season with a lack of forwards, a move to Sydney gives hope Adams can be one of the few 90+ options this season

Comment: Rivers has become a regular in the Dees defence since debuting in 2020 but it took until last season for him to display the potential Fantasy game that he showed in juniors. He increased his average by 24 points to 75, aided by Salem missing games at the start of the season and Brayshaw spending time in the middle at the end. With Harmes and Jordon gone and question marks over Oliver and Brayshaw, Rivers has spent his time in the midfield over the pre-season which is certainly interesting given his junior pedigree. We'll get a proper look in the opening round, but I've just bumped him up the draft order again.
Short: A junior stud who grew in confidence in 2023, rising up the Dees' pecking order for distribution and now we might see him move into the midfield
Nice bounce back, but still scores like a key forward
Back in favour in 2023 and played a nice role off half-back, but scoring reduced as Powell and Atkins were in the team and hard to see him improving on his pre-bye numbers

Comment: Injuries have limited Prestia from fulfilling his Fantasy potential, failing to play 10 games in 2020 and 2021 and playing less than 50% gametime three times in 2022 due to early game injury. However, he played his most games in 2023 since 2019 and didn't have any early injuries, however he averaged his least amount of points since his second season. The injuries might have caught up with him and he's not the player who averaged 105+ in the past.
Short: Had a cleaner run in 2023 but scoring took a hit, not a great sign and already some hamstring issues in 2024

Comment: Holmes has looked the goods in his first three seasons at AFL level, taking a prominent role on a wing and even spent some time inside. He averaged 87 in H1 2023 from 35% CBAs, but this reduced to 67 from 15% in the L5 as he returned to his wing role. Unless he becomes a full-time inside mid and adds some more accumulation to his game, I doubt he'll come into SuperCoach relevance.
Short: A talented player IRL and introduced to CBAs in 2023, however his scoring game has been limited to date

Comment: There was a lot of buzz this time last year for the former Pick 3, and he had a good season without being the competition winning pick we were hoping for. He was used mainly on the wing as it looked as though the Giants were protecting his shoulders which he's had issues with in the past, however was introduced more inside as the season when on. The scoring didn't follow suit and he likely tired playing his first full season. I'm excited to see what he will produce with another pre-season under his belt (his first two were impacted by his foot), and still bullish on his long-term prospects of being a top-end SuperCoach asset, but I doubt we'll see the jump stardom this season that he'll need to produce to be a good mid-pricer.
Short: Future star and hopefully we see him more inside in 2024

Comment: It's hard to know what to make of Simpkin in SuperCoach. After a breakout season in 2020 which saw him increase his average by 22 points per game, he improved again in 2021 by another four points to 97 points per game and 105 post-bye. However, he stagnated in 2022, reducing his average by six despite increased CBAs and then nothing went right in 2023 as he battled with multiple injures and dripped his average by 12 points per game. A hand injury and two concussions saw him have three games with less than 50% game time, with a 12, 24 and 66. Removing those games he averaged 88, so still a level below his best, but it's hard to hit peak form if you miss regular games for injury. A lot of that might have also been due to how bad the Kangaroos were as scores are generally lower for losing teams. The rise of LDU also took some ball off him and with the depth of their midfield now, he spent some time forward. All of these factors are likely to continue, so I doubt he's ever going to become a premium SuperCoach mid. Unless he gets forward status during the season, I think he's going to be more of a Fantasy option than SuperCoach.
Short: 3 injured games last year means he's underpriced, but with Roos struggles and the new depth in the midfield, it's unlikely Simpkin will be an uber mid in SuperCoach

Comment: After seven seasons of in and out of the team(s), playing various roles including as a tall wing, Hinge settled in as an intercepting defender in 2023, playing a career high 22 games and averaging 85. He got better as the season went on, understandably as he got more confidence in his role, and averaged 98 post-bye. His intercepting was a feature, averaging 7.2 per game, compared to the top six defenders 6.5. He'll continue in that role in 2024 and if he can bring the form he showed in the second half of the season, he's 14 points underpriced. He's unlikely to push that to 105+ and be in top six defender contention, which is what he'd need to do to be a worthwhile pick in this limited trades format. I'm not sure I could do it but if you're after a genuine POD in defence, Hinge could be your man.
Short: Breakout season in 2023, averaging 98 post-bye and in AA squad discussions, that level will see him be a top 15 defender despite being ranked 35th on 2023 average
A nice high-mark game-style, but pure outside (29% contested, 23 tackles, 16 clearances) has meant he's never averaged over 100 in SuperCoach and that won't be changing
Scores okay for a small forward but limited in that role

Comment: It looked like the football world was at his feet when he entered the comp with an 90 average. From there, he's battled with injury and being in a struggling team - still yet to play finals in his 12 years in the AFL. I was bullish on him last year as he arrived at the Fantasy-friendly environment at Fremantle with a prominent role in their midfield following Mundy's retirement. However, he just looked old and slow, reducing his average to 80, despite being relatively injury free. It will likely be the Serong, Brayshaw and Young show in 2024 and JOM will be limited to a 'bit' role.
Short: Yet to average 100 in his 12 seasons, and not even a new environment helped that

Comment: The former top 10 pick has had a mixed Fantasy career. After a career high season in 2020 which included a 10 week stretch averaging 118, McDonald's average dropped to just 68 points the season after and hovered in the 70-90 mark since. I know he's the co-captain, but he's far from the accumulator we saw a few years back. With all the injuries, he might even be forced to play tall in 2024. There is some chance he sees a lot of the ball, but I'll need to see it for a few weeks first.
Short: Has it in him to go big as we saw in the back end of 2020, been a role player since but with all the injuries and retirements, could see a bump in 2024

Comment: Former Pick 11 is now a regular at the Dons, playing 41 games in the past two seasons at an average of 79. I think he can play, he's just not in the first group of midfielders at the Dons, reducing his CBAs to 34% last season. That did result in him gaining forward status for 2024, and given how thin the forward line is looking, it's someone like Caldwell who we need to be looking at. Parish and Merrett are the clear main two, but if he looks to leapfrog Setterfield and Hobbs (which I doubt) and be a 60%+ CBA player in the pre-season, he might be a smoky for 2024.
Short: Has talent and forward status keeps him relevant, he just needs to edge out Setterfield and Hobbs for that 3rd man in the Bombers midfield

Comment: Grundy has been on a steady decline - in real life and in SuperCoach- since 2019 when he was the number one SuperCoach player in the comp. He bottomed out last season after thinking it was a good idea to pair up with Max Gawn, seeing him spend a lot of him as a key forward and in the VFL. Common sense prevailed and he got out of there, landing at the Swans where he'll take the solo ruck role. He averaged 100 from Round 2 to Round 5 last season when Max went down, and 93 the year prior. That's a long way off his 130+ glory days of 2018 and 2019, but it's enough at that price to be a great starting pick with the hope the top two rucks come back a bit. If it wasn't for the early bye then there would be no hesitation. Now with the R0 fixture you'll get an idea of how much cash he'll make before Round 5 and I think it will be too much to miss out on.
Short: Not many have a 45 point discount to their career high and while those days are over, he should bounce back to a premium ruck now he's solo again

Comment: The former top 10 pick was well on the radar this time last season following his finish to his debut season and the possibility of increased opportunity inside following the departures of Tom Mitchell and JOM. He spent much of his debut season on the wing, which never bodes well for SuperCoach scoring given the favourable scoring to those with a high contested possession rate. He ended up seeing less inside minutes in 2023 (23% CBAs compared to 38% in his debut season). I certainly didn't expect Nash (69%), Worpel (67%) and Day (63%) to pick up that much of the slack. Of those, Day isn't going anywhere, winning the B&F and showing he's a future star of the comp. Nash came 3rd in the B&F and Mitchell loves him, so his role will likely remain. Newcombe (70%) came second. That leaves Worpel, and my view is that Hawks should move past him and give more minutes to the youngsters in Ward and Mackenzie. I'm not sure that will happen in 2024 though and at that price, he's not an option in SuperCoach. If Day misses the early rounds, we might see it come earlier.
Short: I wrongly picked a breakout last year following and while on a wing he's not going to score great

Comment: Atkins came back from the wilderness in 2023, playing the most games in a season since arriving at the Suns. He actually looked good, scoring over 100 three times in his trademark outside game which involves a lot of short kicks and marks. He was sub or subbed out on three occasions, meaning his average of 72 could have been higher, but that also reflects that he's not locked in the Best 22. At his price, he's certainly not worth the risk.
Short: Was back in the team after just 19 games in three seasons and when conditions suited, scored well, but will be on the fringe again in 2024
MID-only and behind in the pecking order at Geelong, very cheap but I don't think he'll get the opportunity
Always been on my radar for more midfield time one day, but doesn't look like that will happen and scoring has been capped at low-90s as a defender

Comment: Kennedy has a decent SuperCoach game about him, however has long been behind a number of players for midfield spots at the Blues. In 2022, he averaged 97 from 58% CBAs, including a season high of 130 from 76% CBAs when Carlton were missing their first choice mids. However, his CBAs dropped to 34% in 2023 and he found himself on the outer. There were four sub-50% TOG games due to being sub, which resulted in his lowest average for three seasons. As a MID-only and not guaranteed enough inside time, I'm not buying into that discount.
Short: Not attractive as a MID-only option
Reuniting with Ross didn't result in his scores returning to the level under him at Freo and a sub-20% contested rate will always leave him behind in this game
Returned from an ACL but at 34 the former captain is now purely a role player - currently dealing with an eye issue
Gun small forward, talk of mid-time this time last season, but as expected it never eventuated
A medium forward so unlikely to improve his average significantly, unless Hardwick changes up his role

Comment: After a sensational 2022 which saw him beat his previous career best average by over 20, Hewett reduced his average by 32 in his second season at the Blues. He had excuses, injuring his hand in Round 1 on 89 from just 70% game time and then struggled on return. He started as sub in Round 10 scoring 39 and then was subbed off in Round 11 with concussion on 22. He returned as a sub for two games, scoring 19 and 17, before finishing the season playing his typical inside role at the Blues, averaging 99 in the L5. He's pretty important to their structure and often takes the opposition's best mid, so I expect him to stay at over 65% CBAs in 2024 despite their star-studded midfield. His proven to be capable of 100+ in this role, however he'd need to average 105+ again which I doubt he can do. Additionally, the Round 2 bye throws a curveball and for that reason it's hard to consider him in your starting squad.
Short: A down year plagued by injuries following a terrific 2022, or was 2022 just an outlier?
A nice boost last year despite being a forward in a struggling side, but I'm not sure how much higher he could go
Down 14 points on the prior season when he knocked on the door of the top 6, however he's too unreliable for me in SuperCoach with 15 scores under 90 in 2023

Comment: Soldo has played backup to Soldo for his entire career. However, a trade to Port in the off-season should see him become the number one ruck and hopefully see the TOG and CBA levels of other top rucks. He played three full games without Nank in 2023, attending 71%, 72% and 85% CBAs for a 126, 79 and 128. He's shown he can average 100+ number one and at 27, he should be peaking as a ruck. I've got him taking a bit leap in 2023 and maybe in a year without a discounted Gawn, Grundy and Xerri and an early bye, he'd be right in the range for the R2 spot. Add to that, he's missed a big chunk of the pre-season due to a finger injury, so it's likely Sweet will take the number one mantle into the start of the season.
Short: A move to Port should see him take the number one mantle, where he's shown he can score, but a finger injury in the pre-season might open up the door for Sweet to start in that role
Best season IRL since his early days, but a mid-70 average remained including a monster 197 shows he's not a top six chance

Comment: Owens surprised everyone in 2023. The second year player was in genuine rising star conversations in a field which saw two of the best rookies of all time. He did it in a different manner, playing as a medium sized forward, averaging just 15 disposals, but more than half of them contested with over a goal a game. He was used as an inside mid at times in his debut season and as a second ruck last year, which obviously aided his scoring. With Jack Hayes set to return, I doubt we'll see Owens in that second ruck role. So unless we see him back playing some inside mid again, it's hard to see him improving on last year. That is hard to say as typically players take a leap in their third season and Owens is better than your average third year player. He has all the attributes to be a SuperCoach stud in the future, but I think we can rule him out as a starting option if he remains as a forward in the pre-season matches.
Short: Serious talent who does it in an unconventional way, might lose his second ruck minutes to Hayes so unless he turns into an inside mid, where he has been used before, it's hard to see improvement in year 3
Grundy's arrival has squashed any hope of Ladhams having a breakout season, despite showing a nice scoring ability in the VFL

Comment: Berry was highly rated as a junior and showed signs early in his career, however was often hampered by injury. He's had two injury free seasons, however he's been pushed to a wing and his scoring has taken a hit. Since post-bye 2022, he's averaged 6% CBAs. A MID-only with low CBAs isn't what we're chasing. Off-season shoulder surgery doesn't help either as he's had a limited pre-season.
Short: Plays purely on a wing now Dunkley is there which isn't what you want in this game

Comment: Looking back on my comments of past season guides, I've always had hope that Gresham will breakout. He teased us when introduced into the midfield in 2019, averaging 90 after Round 10, but managed just 14 games the next two seasons. He's since split his time between the middle and forward, but Ross Lyon wasn't a fan and played him as a forward, averaging just 22% CBAs post-bye and 7% in the L5. His scoring has been limited due to an unfavourable combination of low contested rate (below 40%) and low efficiency (62%). He now finds himself at the Dons and their midfield is pretty one paced. They've used Jake Stringer in there in the past to add some forward-half damage but he's past it now, and I think there's an opportunity for Gresham to see some time in there. However, he'll need to improve on both of those percentages if he's going to challenge the top six and typically it's hard for those to change.
Short: A new team might see him spend more time in the middle where he's scored okay in the past

Versatile role player who has played almost everywhere, settled into a wing position the last few seasons which hasn't been great for scoring, sounds like he play HB in 2024 which should see improvement but not enough to consider

Comment: After two shocking seasons playing as a forward, JJ finally found his way back to the half-back role where he's averaged 94 and won a Norm Smith in the past. It didn't all go to plan though. A pre-season calf injury saw him start the season slow, getting just six touches in Round 1 and being dropped for Round 2. He returned to play a shutdown role on Charlie Cameron in Round 3 and that was his ticket back to defence. He averaged 91 in his next 6, with three scores over 98, and looked like he was back. However, a significant hamstring injury in Round 10 saw him miss nine weeks. He returned to play two more before an ankle injury finished his season. Hopefully Bevo has taken note and will keep him in his preferred role this this season. That could see him push the 90 mark, which is over 15 points more than he's priced at. But he needs to average 103+ to make the $150k needed to make him a worthwhile mid-pricer given he's not going to be a keeper, and given his career best is 94, I doubt that will happen.
Short: Finally showed the signs of the player who averaged 94 in 2016 with Bevo putting him back where he belongs and injury stopped him from a genuine bounce back

Comment: Big Goldy has been a great SuperCoach ruck over the years. The Roos finally looked to the next generation post-bye last season, where he went from 84% CBAs pre-byes to 56% post. He showed he still has it, averaging 108 when he was the main man early in the season. But after being pushed out to finish the year, he moved to Essendon in the off-season, but even there, I doubt they will use the 35-year-old as their number one ruck.
Short: Now at the Dons, where I think he'll play a mentor role for Draper and Bryan

Comment: After a career best 2021 where he broke into the midfield at stages and looked great, Langford was always on the radar as someone who might break into the midfield full-time. However, he had a disappointing 2022, restricted to just nine games due to hamstring issues, and then used as a marking forward under Scott and to great effect. He kicked 51 goals and made the AA squad, a great effort on a struggling team. He's not going anywhere now after showing how damaging he can be, which means he's not going to be relevant in this game.
Short: Superb season kicking 51 goals and making the AA squad, unfortunately for SuperCoach it means he'll remain in the deep forward role
Showed a bit of a Fantasy game in his early year but been a valuable defensive forward in recent years, I doubt he's the one to see mid minutes with the departures but worth keeping a watch
Has been 79+ in three of last five seasons thanks to playing second ruck, but might see less ruck time with Soldo/Sweet arriving and even his 91 in H1 2023 wouldn't be enough
Been slowly on the decline and 75 from decent midfield time is very low for a former Pick 1, but as a MID-only he hasn't got the upside anymore especially as the Suns look for alternatives inside
Outside wingman with three straight seasons of regression, there's some value there but not as a MID-only with no CBAs

Comment: Bailey has something special about him. However, he might be one of those who are better in real life than in SuperCoach, showcased by a career high average of 83, despite having big impact in some games. The Lions need someone like him to take the next step into the midfield, and he spent more time in there post-bye last year (32%) but that didn't result in a boost in scoring. He did get a 126 when McCluggage missed in Round 14 and he managed 45% CBAs, but it looks like he's not going to make a permanent midfield move anytime soon.
Short: Better in real life than SuperCoach, especially if he remains in this forward/mid role
33-year-old key forward who tops out at the 90 mark

Comment: After averaging 110 post-bye in 2022 following a move to defence, Himmelberg was discussed as an option given he was priced at 80. However, Kinglsey decided to put him back to the forward-line to start the season, and he averaged 67 through eight rounds. The Giants were had just two wins and had to change something up. It was Round 9 where Himmelberg was moved back to defence, however it ended early, out with concussion in the first quarter. So by the time he returned in Round 12, he had an average of 64. From there, he remained in defence and averaged 95. The 110 from 2022 was always going to be a reach, given the more direct style played under Kingsley and that Whitfield and Ash were both used in defence in 2023, so Himmelberg had to share the load. It's been said that the Giants are going to settle Himmelberg as a defender in 2024, which is great news for his SuperCoach prospects and means he's 15+ points under-priced. However, the early bye means it's hard to do, and he'll likely be below the top six anyway.
Short: Didn't hit the heights he did post-bye in 2022 (110), but averaged 95 when moved to defence in 2023 and said to be staying there in 2024
Settled as a forward the last two seasons which has reduced his scoring, but even when as a defender his scoring wasn't high enough to consider at that price and bye
I thought he'd struggle for midfield opportunity last year but the evergreen 33-year-old averaged 91 from 71% CBAs in L5, still not enough to consider at that price, bye and age

Comment: The former Pick 6 had some stints in the midfield last season. He averaged 47% CBAs for the first six rounds of the season and gave the Crows a nice injection of pace in the middle. In that time, he averaged 89 points. Surprisingly, he averaged just 12% CBAs for the rest of the season and 68 points. They preferred Rory Sloane, Ben Keays and later Matt Crouch in there ahead of him. I've said before the Crows' midfield is a little one paced, especially a few years ago when they were running with Laird, Crouch, Berry, Schoenberg and Sloane. Dawson's move in there last year proved a masterstroke and he provided the point of difference, plus they look to have moved on from Berry and Schoenberg. But I think there is still room for the young Rachele to add some spark, and if we get an indication in the pre-season that he'll get 40%+ CBAs, then he could be the mid-priced forward we're hunting for, but it's much harder to take that risk in the limited trade format and based off his role to finish 2023, that might be optimistic.
Short: Got a taste of the midfield early in 2023 with 47% CBAs in first six, dropped off as the season went on but I think the Crows need him in there more
Gun key forward but limited in SuperCoach

Comment: If you've watched Gaff the last three seasons, it's hard to believe he's had multiple seasons over 110. He actually increased his scoring as the CBAs reduced towards the end of the year and I doubt we'll see him in there much at all in 2024, but regardless, it's hard to see him bouncing back to a level worth owning this season.
Short: Hard to believe Gaff was once a premium in this game

Comment: Ross has shown a bit when given the opportunity and dominated at reserve level (113 AFL Fantasy average from three games in 2023, 116 average from three games in 2021) so I think he's got potential to belong at AFL level at one point. However, he's yet to have a proper crack as a midfielder so far. The recruitment of Taranto and Hopper last season didn't help, with Ross attending just 2% of centre bounces for the season. Yze has flagged positional changes, so there's a chance we see Ross get more opportunity in 2024. But it would be too much of a risk at this price point.
Short: Some high scores at VFL level, just hasn't had the inside opportunity at AFL

Comment: Flynn has played 33 games in eight seasons and never played more than 12 in a season. He has always competed for the ruck role at the Giants but now finds himself at West Coast where he should start as their number 1. We've had a decent look at him in that role when he's had the opportunity and he's averaged around the 90 mark. I think he'll get a bit of a boost with some continuity, but I doubt it will be enough to be a worthwhile selection in SuperCoach.
Short: A move to West Coast should see him have a proper run at number one ruck after being in the merry-go-round at the Giants, he might surprise a few

Comment: After being used as a forward and midfielder in his early years, Blakey has now found his own playing as a dashing half-back. He took over the kick-in duties from Jake Lloyd, which shows how much the Swans wanted the ball in his hands and they used him at every opportunity. He cracked the 90 mark in 2023, but I'd need to see more consistency before thinking he can elevate his SuperCoach game to the next level (11 games less than 90 in 2023).
Short: Second season in the running defender role and improved his average again to 90

Comment: Despite an injured eye-socket limiting him to 13 games last season, Stanley still finished the year at the Cats' preferred ruck option, playing nine of the last 10 games at 83% CBAs. With Conway waiting in the wings and Cats' needing to inject some youth into their side in 2024, I wouldn't be surprised to see the 33-year-old pushed out of the side this season.
Short: Surely this is the season they move on from Stanley

Comment: After three terrible seasons where he was injured, in and out of the team and was experimented in different roles, Milera returned to defence last season and showed signs of the 2018 season where he averaged 93 in the last five games. He got better as the season went on, increasing his time on ground, kick-in responsibilities and output as his confidence grew. He looks to have locked up that half-back role for the future, and the 84 he averaged in the L5 games is an indication of what he'll produce going forward. While that makes him slightly underpriced heading into 2024, he's not going to boost his scoring to a level that would make him a worthwhile selection at that price and reach top six numbers, especially with the hamstring issues he has in the pre-season.
Short: Moved back to the HB role in 2023 and got better as the season went on, 84 in L5, but hamstring issues in the pre-season will mean a slow start

Comment: Hollands never got his chance at the Suns after being drafted Pick 7. He managed 116 late in 2022 and looked to have locked away a wing but managed just nine games the following season. Hopefully he gets a chance now he's at the Blues, but he's going to have an interrupted start.
Short: Has shown flashes of talent in the past, but missing the first two weeks and then the early bye will mean a slow start to the season

Comment: The former number 11 pick has been a regular for the Swans since his second season, playing over 90% of the games since. I thought he was a breakout candidate in 2020 after averaging 90 points in his final five games of 2019, however he's stagnated from there. This is on the back of a big drop in CBAs, where he took 69% in the first half of 2020 to 0% last season, where he settled on a half-back flank. Normally a natural midfielder-turned-defender is a recipe for high scoring, but with Blakey and Lloyd taking the majority of the distribution back there, Florent's scoring has remained around the 70 mark. There is scope for some improvement, but with those two still around, I doubt it will consistently be enough.
Short: After looking like a future midfielder with 52% CBAs in 2020, he's now purely a defender (0% CBAs in 2023) in a side with a lot of mouths to feed back there
Obvious Fantasy ability with 138 in VFL last year (135 year prior), just unlikely to have the role at AFL level and low contested rate and efficiency doesn't equate to high SuperCoach scores
A handy winger but most the play goes through the Gulden wing instead

Comment: MacDonald entered the comp with a reputation of being a high production midfielder, his 121 AFL Fantasy average at NAB League was second only to Nick Daicos. He's obviously impressed as he debuted in Round 1 and managed to play 40 games in his first two seasons. So far, he's been limited to a small forward role. I expected him too see some midfield time last season following the departures of Mitchell and JOM, however it never eventuated. He showed improvement over the year, despite the limited role, averaging 61 pre-bye, 76 post and 82 in his L5. He can obviously score, getting 37 touches and 126 AFL Fantasy points in his one VFL game last year. However, at that price you'll need him to average close to the 100 mark to prove a worthwhile selection and he won't do that if he remains as a pure forward. CBAs in the pre-season matches are the key, but he might be one for the future.
Short: A buzz name in the pre-season due to weak forwards, scoring at lower level and natural development

Comment: The Carlton swingman finally had a good run at it last season, playing 22 matches. He looked to have settled as an intercept defender and surprisingly took 62% of the Blues' kick-ins post-bye, ahead of Saad, Newman and Docherty. Intercepting an taking kick-ins is good recipe for success for a SuperCoach defender, however he averaged just 83 in that time which is a long was off the top six defenders in SuperCoach.
Short: A full season after multiple injuries and his intercepts plus kick-ins led to some decent scoring at times

Comment: Was drafted as one of the premier midfielders of the 2020 draft, so after settling with a forward role at the Giants, it was expected he would get his chance at the Cats who, despite being the reigning premiers, were pretty light on in the middle. He arrived at Geelong, who despite being the reigning premiers, they weren't super deep in the mids. He got off to a great start and was very impressive in both pre-season games with a clear inside mid role. He then started well in Round 1, but was then pushed to a wing after Tom Stewart was subbed off. He played 64% TOG that night, then 62% in R2 and 58% R3, none of them sub-impacted games, and then was dropped in R4. This was the story of his season, tastes of inside minutes with 49% CBAs but just 63% TOG. He scored 111 AFL Fantasy points in the VFL game, making it six career VFL games over 100 out of 10, so I think he has the ability. I also think Geelong need to buy into their rebuild and give players like Bruhn more opportunity. However, I'm not confident it will happen so while he's a breakout candidate, I'm not 100% sold on him.
Short: Had a taste of midfield time in his first season at the Cats but CBA and TOG always capped, boost this year?

Comment: Corey Wagner was on both North Melbourne and Melbourne's list before being picked up by Freo from the VFL where he averaged 84 AFL Fantasy points. He got off to a shaky start, playing two games in the first six weeks and then not playing again until Round 18. However, he played the final seven games at an average of 80. That's about his level, but given his scrappy foot-skills, I'm not sure he'll be a lock in Freo's 22 each week.
Short: Mature age draftee took a while to find his groove back at AFL level but played the last seven at an average of 85

Comment: Harmes is coming off an average of 46 where played just nine games (was sub on three occasions). He's been a solid SuperCoach contributor in the past, averaging 80 in 2022, 86 in 2021 and 95 in 2019. So when he arrived at the Dogs with forward status, in a year lacking forwards, he gained immediate interest. He's priced at $258k, which means he'll need to average approximately 75 to make 25k. Given he's done this in three of the last five seasons (3 of the four before last), there's a high likelihood that he will prove a good mid-priced pick. And given the forwards are so light on, and that the Dogs don't have an early bye, it's a punt I'm willing to take.
Short: Now at the Dogs and who knows what Bevo has planned for him, if it's a midfield role he can return to his 80+ ways which makes him a very attractive mid-priced prospect

Comment: Perryman had been a reliable wing/midfielder for the Giants since 2019, averaging 90+ for the three season to 2022 and slowly spent some more time inside (including a season high 138 from 51% CBAs in the first game after Leon left). He started in the opening centre bounce of 2023, however injured his hamstring in the opening minutes on 1, forcing him to miss the next four weeks. He returned in Round 6 and had 79% CBAs, so he was obviously in Kingsley's plans to play as a midfielder. However, he moved back to defence after Round 10, seeing CBAs in just one other match for the season. This coincided with Giants getting on a roll, so you'd think he will remain in that role in 2024. He averaged 73 in this time, so while he comes into 2024 with defender status, discounted due to his early injury and 19 points below his career best, it's unlikely he'll improve on his 2023 average if his post-bye role and scoring are anything to go by.
Short: Returned to defence post-bye when Giants started to roll, so you'd think his wing/midfield days are done along with those 90+ scores

Comment: Stocker got a life-line from the Saints and was great for them in 2023, playing 23 matches as a small defender. While he scored okay, he's behind Sinclair, NWM and even Battle for distribution and limited to a defensive role. Saints do possess the ball in their D50 which will keep his score up, but it's hard to see him improving much on his 2023 average.
Short: Career best season playing 23 games, but low in the pecking order for distribution at the Saints
Averaged 85 last season having a terrific year IRL, it's hard to see him reaching much higher

Added plenty to the Giants after missing the entire 2022 season, pushes up to stoppages so he scores better than the average small forward but I doubt he's ever going to make the genuine midfield transition needed to be relevant in this game
Terrible injury history, however he had his first consistent season with 17 matches and showed great signs intercepting in defence, but scoring isn't there as a key defender

Comment: Elliot Yeo was a Fantasy premium in 2018 averaging 107, making him the 15th highest scorer in the comp. He backed that up with a respectable 105 but then the dreaded OP struck, and he's missed more than 50% of games since and struggled with his output. A calf injury just before Round 1 after looking the goods as a midfielder in the pre-season games wasn't the ideal start. He then played two games before Round 11 after dealing with groin issues, averaging just 50. However, he started to find his groove, averaging 101 for the four games to Round 15, before hurting his hip - the trifecta! He went on to play four more games, but was managed throughout, including being used as the sub. All that together left with a 80 average for the season. If he's healthy, he can easily average 100+, whether that's as a defender in the absence of Shannon Hurn or as a mature inside mid. Him being healthy is the big question and a risk that anyone will take who pick him. In the limited trade format where you really need him to be a top six defender to be a decent selection, he's too much of a risk for me. Update: He's fit (for now), he's full time mid and I'm on board.
Short: Hasn't played more than 12 games in the last four seasons so his body is always a concern, but if fully fit he's still a very good player IRL and SuperCoach and all reports he is

Comment: After years on the fringe, Guthrie has now played 44 games in the last two seasons, cementing his spot in backline. He had some nice scoring games when Geelong play their high marking style in defence, but I doubt hell ever average enough to be considered in SuperCoach.
Short: Now a regular for the Cats but not one for SuperCoach
Showed promise averaging 80 in just his third season, but never took the next step and now a MID-only now coming off a sub-60 average post-bye on a wing
Turned into a gun intercept defender IRL and shown a ceiling with Freo's high mark game in defence (3 scores over 120 in 2023), but a season average of 88 isn't enough to consider
Crazy to think he averaged 107 in 2018, now 30 and with the Saints looking to add more speed, he might struggle for opportunity in 2024

Comment: Baker does a bit of everything for the Tigers, playing forward, back and even in the middle. He can excel at all of them and if we knew he would remain a defender or a mid then we might be able to trust him in Fantasy. Yze has flagged positional changes, so despite the inconsistency to date, he's on my watchlist for the pre-season. He's a far better player than his career best average of 83.
Short: He can certainly play, but too hard to predict where he'll play week-to-week, maybe we'll get some consistency with role in 2024 and he beats that 83 career best average

Comment: There was a bit of buzz around Lipinski when he arrived at the Pies. He showed great signs from limited opportunities at the Dogs and put up some monster scores at VFL level. He led the Pies for CBAs in the pre-season game and then scored 133 from 48% CBAs in Round 1. However, he didn't go on with it and dropped to 19% in his last five of 2023. He was completely pushed out of the midfield last season, attending just 3% CBAs for an average of 70. The structure obviously worked as the Pies went on to win the flag. Adams is gone but he didn't see many CBAs either, so I doubt Lipinski will get back in the middle in 2024.
Short: Forward status is nice but doubt he'll get the midfield opportunities he needs to be a top six as he had just 3% last year when Pies won the flag
Gun key forward, just not Fantasy relevant with an average in the 70s in each of his last three seasons

Comment: Coleman moved to defence in 2022 after averaging 109 AFL Fantasy points in the role at reserve level in 2021. He showed he has the makings to be a star defender of the future, but injures stopped him from a full breakout. The story was much the same in 2023. He was concussed in Round 1 on 69, forcing him to miss Round 2. He returned to average just 63 in his next nine to the bye, looking a shadow of the player that broke out a year earlier. He was so far out of form that he started as sub post-bye, which is where he scored his 29. After that, he was quoted saying "I just thought to myself to back myself. Thats when I play my best footy, when Im just out there, playing freely and playing on instinct". And he did. He averaged 90 in his last seven matches, which included another injury (eye) when saw him sit off just after half time and miss two more matches. He then went to another level in the finals, averaging 102, including a best on ground performance in the prelim and 22 disposals to half time (over 100) in the GF. While Rich was a non-factor last year, his retirement means that Coleman is now the number one distributor for the Lions, a role which can yield an 95+ average. However, he'll need to push the 100 mark to be a worthwhile mid-priced selection in this format. If it weren't for the Round 2 bye, I'd be prepared to start with him, but I don't think I can with that bye.
Short: Interrupted 2023 but his finish caught the eye (97 in L3, 106 in finals) and he comes in as a nice, discounted defender, if it wasn't for that Round 2 bye
Handy scorer for a key defender (helps that he takes 61% of the KI - not many full-backs do that) but not enough to make him relevant
Has played a vital role as a hard running small forward at West Coast for a number of years now, just not a great role for SuperCoach scoring
No shortage of distributors in defence at the Dons so I doubt we'll suddenly see an increase in average anytime soon, despite four sub games built into it

Comment: Sam Berry looked like he was the future of the Crow's midfield, playing prime midfield minutes in his second season over the likes of leadership group member Ben Keays and former B&F winner Matt Crouch. He led the comp in tackles per game, which was a great achievement for a 21-year-old in his first full season in the midfield. However, Berry's 17.6 disposals per game was low for a main midfielder and with Laird already offering tackle pressure (number two on the tackle list that year), the Crows looked to add some more speed and dynamic movement in there last season. That meant Berry spent most of the year playing SANFL, with just four games at AFL level after 35 in his first two seasons. Laird and Dawson are locked into the midfield and they opted for Crouch as the third mid to finish 2023. I doubt much will change this season, but hopefully we see more of Berry in 2024. If we do, he just needs to average 70 to make $150k and we know he can do that, so he's certainly worth considering.
Short: An 87 in his second season looked like he'd be a future stud, but the Crows have gone quicker inside now leaving him on the outer

Comment: Once a star IRL, but struggled with form and injury at the Dons. He's had foot and knee surgery in the off-season and together with the number of young mids emerging at the Essendon, I doubt we see him in their midfield again.
Short: Out of favour at the Dons who now have plenty of young options to take the midfield spots

Comment: Fisher could never quite crack it at the Blues, despite being always spoken of highly by key members of the team. He was traded to North in the off-season in a trade that could really unlock his potential. After playing just one of 13 games from Round 8, the small forward came back into the side in Round 21 as a running half-back. He had 32 disposals in that game and remained there for the next 3, before being dropped for finals. Around the trade, Fisher noted that Clarkson earmarked him to play as a running defender at the Roos as they look to add to their run and carry game. We've seen the primary Roo defender rack up Fantasy points in recent years, from Luke McDonald in 2020, Jack Ziebell and Aaron Hall in 2021 and Harry Sheezel last season. With Hall and Ziebell retired and Sheezel a chance to progress into the midfield, Fisher is every chance to land that role. At his price, he'll need to average 96 for the $150k to make him a good mid-priced selection. He managed 86 in that role at the Blues, but he had Newman and Saad taking a lot of the distribution off him. I think he'll fall just short of the 96, but he's not a bad option give he might not be far behind the F6. Update: That role was there but he's now had two hamstring issues which is a red flag, I am okay taking on an injury risk like Yeo, but interrupted pre-season is another issue.
Short: Might not have seen like much at the time, but could be a very relevant off-season move if he lands himself in the plumb distribution role at the Roos, but multiple hamstring issues in the pre-season is a red flag
A gun full-back of the comp but not a relevant pick in this game
Better IRL than in SuperCoach, Quaynor is a gun small defender but yet to show he's much of an accumulator so his scoring is limited

Comment: Cumming dropped his averaged by 26 points in 2023, which was amazing given there was no injury and he was heading into his age 24 season, meaning he should be in his prime. Cumming averaged 95 in 2022 and his breakout 2021, quickly becoming the Giants' number one distributor down back as Leon played Ash on the ball and Whitfield up forward. Kingsley came in and put things straight, with Whitfield and Ash back in defence and later Himmelberg who moved back to finish the season. This pushed Cumming up to a wing, which as we know isn't a good thing for Fantasy scoring. He averaged 65 post-bye and didn't take a kick-in to finish the year. This coincided with the Giants' best form of the year, so I'm not sure there is a spot for Cumming in defence in 2024, at least not the high distribution role he had in 2022. I'm not banking on a large bounce back this season at least.
Short: Not many 25-year-olds drop 26 points per game without an injury, has to bounce back but no longer the main distributor with Whitfield, Ash and Himmelberg back now
Struggled to get on the park since 2019, his best is decent for a key back but even that wouldn't be enough

Comment: JHF impressed in his first season at the Power. He arrived after one season at the Roos where he had 40% CBAs. With Wines, Boak, Butters, Rozee and Drew, I doubted he would see more than this for a team in contention, however he finished with 59% CBAs to be a clear first-choice midfielder. If you're looking at pure disposal stats, you'd say he had a modest season, averaging less than 18 touches per game. However, he finished the year with 16 Brownlow votes, the same as sensation Tom Green. He tore some games apart with his clearance work and penetration inside 50 from stoppages. However, he lacked consistency and easy possessions. He had nine games sub 70. He's yet to have a full pre-season, so maybe that explains why he doesn't do much outside of a stoppage. But he's in the Patrick Dangerfield mold, and Danger took four seasons before he averaged over 80. I expect him to add some more disposals to his game this year. However, with Wines hoping to spend more time inside also, I don't think we'll see a significant bump from JHF this year.
Short: Clear talent but in the high impact low disposals bucket at the moment, his first full pre-season might see him win more ball but I think he'll need a few more years before his best

Comment: The former top 10 pick averaged had two x 110 scores in the last seven games of his 2nd season and was heavily involved in centre bounces. He hasn't come on from there, failing to average above 81. Hes also had a shocking run of injuries, and while he managed 19 matches last season, he missed six weeks in the middle with a knee injury when he was on 3. He was also sub on a few occasions, with four games under 50% TOG. The positive was that he was injected back into the midfielder, with 31% CBAs from his 58% season TOG. The downside is that he lost his defender status, which is what kept him on my radar his whole career. A clean run of injury will see a nice improvement in output in 2024, as his ranked 103rd in price yet 36th for points per minute. But he's too risky of a play as a MID-only option.
Short: Has ability but battled with injuries his whole career and now lost the defender status that always kept him relevant

Comment: Sholl finished 2020 with an adjusted 111 and 90 and was the designated kicker at the Crows. He then had a 160, 103 and 91 in his first five games of 2021 and looked to be a serious player of the future. It all went downhill from there and Sholl has struggled for senior opportunities since. I've seen enough to believe he'll be a player in the future, but as a midfield only option in SuperCoach he's not an option this year.
Short: Wing with MID-only status yet to cement his spot in the team

Comment: I just like the way this guy goes about it and was surprised he was pushed out of the midfield rotation for the likes of Crouch and Keays to finish the season. I think he's a star of the future, but it won't be this year if he stays at 9% CBAs. I wouldn't start with him, but just keep him on your radar. A pre-season ankle injury might delay that further.
Short: I really like this guy and he could be the breakout player we're chasing, but MID-only for someone who had 9% CBAs post-bye makes it hard
Key defender with limited scoring

Comment: The number nine pick of the 2020 draft has played an impressive 61 games in his first two seasons, providing some x-factor around goal and in the air. Hes been tested in the middle at times and looked okay, but I would've expected more than 62 from his 39% CBAs post-bye. He just doesn't look like a big ball winner. The Bombers have a number of players who run through there, and I currently have Perkins behind Hobbs and Caldwell ahead of him, so I can't see him keeping up that 39%. However, with his forward status hes worth keeping an eye on.
Short: A watch on his CBAs in pre-season and forward status makes him relevant, but we could say that about a number of Bombers
Drafted top 10 in 2018 as a midfielder, although limited to defence and the wing at AFL and scoring hasnt been there consistently
One of the best restrictive small defenders in the comp, but not in a scoring friendly role
Star key forward but scoring will always be limited
Genuine role player in defence who has capped out at the 80 mark
Star small forward hasn't done much more than 70 in that role, but supposedly training as a half-back which could provide a small boost

Comment: Was said to be the premier midfielder and the most ready to play from the 2020 draft pool. Phillips for Oakleigh averaged better numbers at the same age during the finals than Matt Rowell and Noah Anderson. However, he didn't look it in his first season, averaging 48 in his 14 games. He then missed the entire 2022 season due to glandular fever, but completed a full pre-season in 2023. He got enough opportunity, 16 games at 62% CBAs, however didn't take the jump I was hoping he would. The Roos' midfield developing nicely, I wouldn't be surprised to see Philips on the outer in 2024.
Short: Highly credentialed junior was finally fully fit in 2023 after glandular ruined his 2022 season, however didnt show much and might be overtaken by the new batch of Roo mids
On a wing now and that combined with his age means he's not the 90+ scorer of the past

Comment: Jones has been used as a dashing half-back for the depleted West Coast side in the last two seasons and showed flashes of decent scoring, including an 84 average from Round 4-8. I like him there and think he adds something different to a Witherden and Hough type, but there's no certainty of his spot in the side so it's hard to take a punt on him, especially with a pre-season hamstring.
Short: Averaged 92 from Round 4-8 before injury stuck and he might find it harder this season as WC have a healthier list

Comment: Draper is a ruck who is better IRL than in SuperCoach. He might see more than 66% CBAs now that Phillips has retired, but then again Goldy might be the preferred man. Judging from his scoring to date, it's hard to see him making an impact in SuperCoach, despite ruckmen typically hitting their peak at age 25.
Short: I know even the best SuperCoach rucks take time, but Draper has now had seven seasons at AFL level and yet to average 80, an interrupted pre-season isn't going to help either

Comment: Sparrow has been getting midfield opportunities in a strong midfield since his debut. The scoring hasn't followed suit, averaging 67 from 46% CBAs in 2023 after 63 from 32% CBAs in 2022. He's obviously highly rated and there is more time up for grabs with Jordon and Harmes gone and Oliver's situation, however I doubt we will see his scoring spike much more than 75.
Short: Mid-forward who gets CBAs but yet to show a scoring game

Comment: Scim has a SuperCoach game that I thought would see him be a top six defender before his career is done. However, he's now 25 and yet to average over 84. His teammates have scored well in a similar role and I think have move passed him now, so I'm now less bullish.
Short: I've been a fan of the former top 10 pick for a few years now but he just hasn't delivered, starting to lose hope
At his best, the interceptor pushed the top 6, but hasn't been that way for a while now and five sub games in 2023 indicate they might have moved past him
Even when number one ruck he wasnt a Fantasy scorer and I think the Blues prefer PitBull in CBAs as they did as the season went on
One of the best small forwards in the comp but still not one for SuperCoach, despite the fact he takes CBAs of those that are relevant
Yet to match his brilliant debut season, a new team might provide a fresh start but with MID-only, it's not worth punting on the bounce back
A reliable defender but scoring is capped at 70
Key forward/ruck who had his best year to date but scoring won't be enough
Struggled with injury and other health issues in 2023 so scoring was down, can definitely outperform his price but probably not by enough to be relevant

Comment: Campbell showed a lot of promise early as a rookie, scoring 96 in his second game. He's got a terrific kick on him and showed enough for me to think he'll be a player of the future. However, he played 23 matches last season and averaged just 69, so I think it will be a while before he comes SuperCoach relevant with Blakey and Lloyd controlling things down back.
Short: Elite kick and has talent, but yet to show much in the scoring department so far
Back after two years overseas last season and looked as good as ever, but that just yields a 63 point average
Can play forward, back, and ruck and it looks like he's settled in the least scoring-friendly role, defence

Comment: Zurhaar is a bash and crash forward, a powerful athlete and shares some (very minor) similarities with Petracca. A move to the midfield has always been on the cards and that evolution started last year with a career high 22% CBAs. It didn't lead to a spike in scoring, increasing his average by six to 69. He's reportedly much leaner this season and set for a big season, but we've heard that before. If anything I can see him being a high impact mid/forward, but I doubt he's suddenly going to become an accumulator.
Short: We've been waiting for the strong forward to make a 'Petracca' midfield move, which kind of happened last year to no real effect but supposedly has stripped fitter this season

Comment: Really liked what I saw from Weddle, both defensively and his rebound from defence and there is plenty of high praise for him coming out of Hawthorn. The Hawks have found one. However, it's hard to rely on a rebounding defender who doesn't take kick-ins and is behind Sicily, Hardwick and Amon for distribution. One for the future.
Short: Terrific debut season and a player for the future, natural improvement should come but still behind a few for distribution so he's hard to rely on
Found more opportunity with Amon leaving, playing a career high 22 games, but scoring remained in the 70s

Comment: After sitting behind Goldstein for many years, it looked like North had finally decided to look to the future when they named Xerri sole ruck in Round 1 and Goldy emergency. After getting off to a flyer (35 points in 15% TOG), he did his syndesmosis and missed the next 15 weeks. After 113 AFL Fantasy points in the VFL, he returned to the senior side again as sole ruck, seeing 84% CBAs for a 102.. He was sole ruck the following week but found things tougher against the Reeves/Meek duo (many did in 2023) and scored 75. However he was never solo again, averaging 43% CBAs for the final six matches sharing with Goldy. Goldy has now been moved on and we should see Xerri solo for 2024. He has the scoring ability and now should have the opportunity and with no early bye like the other value ruck plays (Gawn and Grundy). The difference between him being a nice value play in AF and a R2 option in SC is that you're going to need him to either be a keeper (which is very unlikely - 115 average) or at least average enough to earn 150k, which is 101. With the inflated scoring rucks get in this game, 101 is on the lower end of my projections, so I think we'll see him make the 150k. Update: face surgery will keep him out of contact training for a few weeks, but he should still be able to keep up his fitness.
Short: Started Round 1 sole ruck but an early injury meant he never had a proper crack at it, with Goldy now gone, it's Xerri time
Amazing season finishing 7th in the Coleman and still averaged 70 shows how low key forwards score in this game

Comment: After averaging 84 in his second season, Burton looked to be a star Fantasy defender of the future. He hasn't matched that average since. Unfortunately, he hasn't come on and you can't take the risk on him turning it around this year.
Short: Hasn't come on as I thought he was going to after his 84 average in year 2

Comment: So far in his career, he's been more of an impact player than an accumulator, which is never a great thing for SuperCoach scoring. We've all been waiting for him to pop and be the explosive, goal kicking mid the Lions are crying out for, but just 8% CBAs last year after 24% the year before, the Lions might now see him as just a forward. Even if those CBAs rise I'd want to see some sign of scoring improvement first. 10 Feb Update: Sounds like the midfield move is going to happen, I've moved him up slightly but nothing of note just yet.
Short: Still waiting for the breakout and CBAs just 8% after 24% the season prior not a good sign
The junior stud with Rockliff-like NAB League numbers has been limited to a small forward role at AFL level (0% CBAs in last two seasons) and hard to see that changing
Had a huge improvement in his first year a the Giants but small forward roles aren't friendly for scoring
Star small forward but scoring limited to sub-80
Star key defender in real life, scores decently in SC but a bit off the top 6
Role player for the Blues not in SuperCoach calculations, unfortunately has done an ACL and will miss the season
Limited to a 60 average while in the forward role and given how good he is at it, I doubt we'll see him back on the wing or half-back again
Regular role player in defence for the Saints but never taken his game to the next level in SuperCoach
Very good footballer but scoring limited as a small forward, so unless he make a move to the midfield which he's teased at times, he's not going to make an impact in SuperCoach

Comment: Saints look like they got a steal with Windhager, taken pick 47 of the 2021 draft. After an impressive debut season, Windhager was made to work for his opportunities in his second season. A broken hand in the pre-season match saw him miss Round 1 and then start as the sub in Round 2. He was sub in three of the his first six matches before being dropped to the VFL. It's here he showed his scoring power, scoring 98, 157, 91 and 120 AFL Fantasy points in his four matches. This shouldnt come as a great surprise considering he scored over 110 AFL Fantasy points twice in three games at the level in 2022. He was back in the senior side in Round 13 and didn't miss a game after that. He moved to the half-back in Round 17 and played there for the final nine games of the season, averaging 76. Personally I found the move odd as the one knock on him is his kicking, he's certainly better suited inside mid. However, it means he has defender status heading into 2024 and if the inside mid move happens, he could prove one of the value picks of the season and I can see him making his 150k. However, if he remains in defence, it's unlikely to happen given what he showed as a defender. Big pre-season watch.
Short: Played a bit of everywhere in his first two seasons and shown above average ability, I'm a believer I just need to see his role in the pre-season
Had his best season in five years but not enough to be relevant
Small forward who has been used in spurts in the middle, but scoring is still capped at sub-70
A 2021 mid-season draft pick has made the wing his own, much loved by Bomber supporters but scoring is limited on the wing
Evergreen 35-year-old full forward is still playing well IRL but not the combo you want in SuperCoach
Has talent but hovers around the 60-mark every season
Ignore the discount to career high (which was four games in the 16-min quarters), he plays a more defensive role nowadays
Had some good games last season for someone who was delisted the re-rookied, but scoring wasn't enough to consider this season

Injuries kept him to just eight matches last season, meaning he's pretty cheap but he'd need to eclipse his career best season by six to be worthwhile and that will be hard to do following his injury woes
Small forward who played 22 matches last season, but role isn't what you want in SuperCoach

Horror season playing four matches before injury ruled him out, priced at 52 meaning a 80+ averaged will make him 150k, but at 31 and off an interrupted pre-season, I'm not sure he can get to 80+ in a rebuilding team

Comment: After a very impressive first season and a 151 in Round 2 of his second, it appeared that Bowey could be a SuperCoach gem. However, he's yet to replicate that output at AFL level since, averaging just 70 in the last two seasons. Hes showed enough to suggest hes going to be a gun in the future, but hes behind a few at the Dees so it wont be for a few years yet.
Short: Showed flashes of scoring potential in his 47 games to date but just doesn't do it regularly enough
Rallied strongly since being delisted and re-rookied but consecutive seasons averaging low-60s isn't what we're after
35-year-old has been a gun in the past - IRL and SuperCoach - but will again play a mentor role at the Power
Disappointing last two seasons after a career best 2021 - form, fitness and role too hard to predict
Key position player and scoring is stuck in the 60-70 range
His 101 VFL average in 2022 didn't translate to his AFL in 2023 as he spent most of the season on the wing
Genuine role player, either in defence or as a tagger, and scoring has never been relevant

Comment: After an impressive debut season, Hough took a while to find his groove in 2023 with injury keeping him to two games after the first eight rounds. He then played all bar two the rest of the season, which included a 107, which is impressive given his age, role (defender with 1% KI) and how poor West Coast were. Shannon Hurn retiring is going to open up a lot of distribution opportunities down back at West Coast and Hough could well be the one who benefits. At that price point, it's hard to take a punt on him though, but he could be one for the future.
Short: Has displayed a nice kick-mark game in his first two seasons and with Hurn's departure freeing up some distribution, we could see him get a nice bump in 2024
Settled in a defensive forward role now and plays it to great effect, so the days of waiting for the midfield move might be over
The wing/half-forward has a bit about him and I think he can be a good player, but not a Fantasy one if he continues in those roles
A role change last season from a reliable 80s defender to a pressure forward wasn't good for his SuperCoach output and even if he switches back his upside isn't enough

Comment: There has been limited exposed form for Wardlaw over the last two year, but what we have seen has been outstanding. He was limited to just four games in his draft year due to hamstring injuries but of those, was best on ground in Round 1 and BOG again in the AFL Academy game. He was on a modified pre-season program and didn't debut until Round 10, but it was one of the better debuts you'll see - 16 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 63% TOG. He backed it up in Round 13 with 22 touches, six clearances and nine tackles from 70% TOG and 22 touches and seven tackles from 68% in Round 16. However, he was a late out Round 17 and subbed out in Round 18 and then played just the one more game for the year where he again had nine tackles in 55% TOG. In all he finished the season with eight matches at just 60% TOG. He's now had his first full pre-season under his belt which should see him bump up to at least 70% TOG. At the same PPM, he would average 78, which isn't enough. Daicos's 2nd year breakout was another level given he came off a high base but Clayton Oliver and Tim Taranto were at a similar price point where you can afford to wait to see how they look (role, TOG, score) in the early rounds and trade them in if they tick the boxes. That's how I'll play it I think.
Short: Caught the eye in limited opportunities in his debut season and looks a future star, second year breakouts are rare but he's one who could be up to it
Medium forward with limited scoring opportunities

Comment: Graham appeared to be the next midfielder up once Cotchin, Prestia and Martin start to push out. And given his elite tackling ability and scoring at junior level, he's one I've kept an eye on. After seven scores over 100 in 2021, including a massive 154, and 40% CBAs in the last 5, I expected that transition to happen in 2022. However, he went backwards, averaging 75 from just 22% CBAs (incl. 48 from 1% in his last 5) and 66 from 6% last season. A new coach provides hope that he might be seen in the middle again, but it's not a punt I'd be willing to take.
Short: Arrival of Taranto and Hopper quashed any hope of Graham stepping up in the midfield, but maybe the new coach will be the change he needs

Comment: Reeves proved the hardest ruck for opposition players to ruck against. He's a very strong hitout ruck, but struggles to impact around the ground which, between that and sharing the duties with Meek, caps his output.
Short: Meek arriving put question marks on his spot but he emerged the preferred option and will likely be the Hawks' number one ruck to start, but will share duties at times which will cap his output
Wing/forward who has had his opportunities but has never scored well enough

Played 18 games in his first season at North but limited to a wing which is never good for scoring, has scored okay when inside in the past but with the young midfield depth developing at the Roos I can't see him used there
Averaged 83 post-bye incl finals when his kick-in duties went from 3% to 21% and with some more confidence can improve again, but not to a level worth considering

Comment: Bowes was a prolific midfielder in juniors, averaging 118 AFL Fantasy points in the NAB League which saw him be a top 10 pick at the Suns, where he played predominantly in defence. He looked to arrive in 2021, averaging 104 in the first eight games, but has battled with injury ever since. A hamstring injury stopped his breakout in 2021 and then surgery in the pre-season ruled him out for the first four months of 2022. He arrived at Geelong last season and looked to have a mid role in the first pre-season game before a hamstring injury saw him just play a half. After missing Round 1, he played five matches with only one with CBAs. He then hurt his calf on 15 and missed the next six weeks. He returned as sub for the next three matches, scoring 17, 41 and 25. He's hard to read as is the Cats, who played him back, wing, on-ball and forward in 2023. If he can settle in a position he might prove a great pick, but he hasn't been reliable so far in his career so it's too risky for me.
Short: Didn't get the mid time we expected after moving to the Cats and even when he did, he didn't catch the eye but a full pre-season and four sub games means he's underpriced heading into 2024
Likely out for the season with an Achilles
Become a decent forward after many wrote him off, but key forwards aren't what we're looking for
Small forward and getting on in age at 33
Not quite a key position player but scores like one
A life-line at the Dogs saw him play 18 matches last season, but wing role kept his scoring in check
Key forward developing into a very nice player, but not in SuperCoach
Managed to break in as a defender and looked the goods as a designated kicker, but scoring not enough to consider this season
Showed signs of why he was taken Pick 1 in 2020 and I feel like he could rip the comp apart this season, but breakouts for key position forwards aren't enough in this game
Former first rounder played every game in 2023 and highly rated, but might need some more time before we see consistent scoring (22 games of 24 under 90)
Had an incredible year in a struggling side but still not scoring enough to be anywhere near relevant

Comment: Is there a 28 gamer that has had more airtime in Fantasy than Braydon Preuss? After missing his full first season at the Giants, Preuss averaged 100 points per full game played. It was the fact he only played 10 games and got injured/suspended/dropped throughout the year. Sadly, this has been the consistent story for Preuss his entire career and it allowed Briggs to take the number one mantle last season and run with it. There's no doubt he's a very good Fantasy scorer when on the park, but I think he'll just got back to dominating the VFL (107 AFL Fantasy average last season, 132 in 2019).
Short: Had his chances but never took them and now Briggs has cemented the number one ruck role at the Giants
Outside wing who has amazingly averaged in the sub-72 the whole way through under Hardwick's style, might change with a new coach but as a MID-only he's not going to be an option
Gun key defender but is now 33 and hard to see a relevant jump in scoring

Comment: The former number three pick looked set to fulfill his potential in 2019, pushing up the ground to average 99 points per game, including 106 in the last half. Unfortunately, he hasn't gone on with it, dropping his average in every season since to finish on 62 last year from just three matches after a broken leg ruled him out for the first half of the season. At 28, he should be in his prime and may appear underpriced to what he could produce and an off-season move to the Dees might change things for him. It will be very interesting to see how the Dees use him. On the watch-list for the pre-season and I guess we'll get a proper indication in the opening round. All he needs is an average of 72+ to prove a worthwhile pick at that price, which he's done every season outside of his debut and his last. I think I'm on board.
Short: Reduced his average every year since 2019 where he was a top six forward, a change of scenery might be what he needs to turn it around
Been on the radar since his elite junior numbers (124 average in NAB League) but limited to a forward role at AFL level and always on the fringe
Moved to Hawks last season for more opportunity but found himself playing second fiddle to Reeves, and given how good Reeves was, it will likely continue in 2024
Took the number one ruck mantle for finals and finished with a premiership, but that didn't lead to much of a bump in scoring
Returned from an ACL to play 12 matches in 2023 but not as the midfielder he needs to be to be relevant in this game
A key position player who would score a bit higher if he kicked straighter, but not enough to make an impact
Been a good servant of all three teams but I think he'll struggle for opportunities this season with the young Roo mids emerging
74 in 2020 the outlier, he's been a mid-50s guy his whole career which is what you can expect from a small forward
Key defender who might see some more opportunity with Murray injured, but he scores like a full-back
Had some good games in 2023 and I think we'll see a lot more of him, but small forward role isn't conducive to scoring
General defender who outside his 110 score in 2023, doesn't generate enough points to be relevant
Lock-down defender who is currently dealing with an ankle injury
Was preferred over TDK for number one ruck and proved hard to ruck against, but scoring limited
Scores okay in the ruck (season high 116 from season high 47% CBAs) and reportedly wants more time in there this season, but hard to see that happening when they have the All-Australian there
A small forward with a bit of energy about him, not one for the Fantasy scorers though
Will hope to bounce back from a career worst season but even best case won't be enough, especially with a pre-season hamstring

Comment: Former Pick 11 battled with injury in his first few seasons at the Crows but played 21 last season and looked the part with his strong body and skills. He was used primarily as a small forward, but was introduced to the midfield with 13% CBAs across the season. I think he's going to be a regular midfielder in the future, but I also think Rachelle and Soligo will. And Laird and Dawson aren't going anywhere this season. So while I think one of the young guns will breakout this season, I'm not sure I'm ready to punt on any of them.
Short: Another of the young Crow fwd/mids who has shown enough to suggest they will be future guns, and he was preferred over Rachelle and Soligo for CBAs in the backend of 2023
Showed amazing running power on the wing for a first-year player and can see him staying on the wing for the Blues for the future, which isn't great for his scoring
Hard running forward is a regular at Freo but role isn't great for SuperCoach
Dropped 14 points from his B&F season but even that wasn't worth owning in SuperCoach

Comment: Ginbey was one of the few shining lights for West Coast in 2023.
