He was thrown in the deep end playing inside mid for a team who struggled most weeks, but it was a clear sign they have big wraps on the kid. He showed a great tackle ability (5.9 per game, in line with the top eight mids) and contested possession rate (46.4%, above that of the top eight mids), however struggled to win the ball outside the contest (13.7 disposals and 1.5 marks per game). That will come, but I doubt it will see a big spike in his second season. He's in great condition on the training track and I'm looking forward to see how he looks in the pre-season games, but out of the second year players, I don't think he's the one that will have the big impact.
Short: Big bodied mid has got even bigger this off-season and could certainly breakout, just not sure he has the outside game to be a worthy Fantasy option just yet
Will be a star key forward someday but scoring isn't there
Back after three years out and at that price he's worth considering at R3 if named but he's likely just back-up in case anything happens to Nank
Medium forward who found a role on the wing to finish 2023, but scoring wasn't great
The strong tackling mid has been out with an ACL and expected to miss the start of 2024

Comment: Out of all the 2020 draftees, I was most impressed with Powells first season, which makes his last two seasons even more disappointing. The former Pick 13 averaged 68 in his first season after 35 disposals per game in SANFL Under-18s in his draft year. He's since been in and out of the side and averaged 56 points per game in the last two seasons. He got a bit of a bump in midfield time, which included 29% CBAs post-bye to net a 68 average. He will remain on the radar given he has forward status and talent at junior level, however with another batch of young players coming in at the Roos, it's going to be harder for him in 2024 to get the opportunity. However, he's apparently dominating the pre-season, so once again he's on my watchlist for 2024 - without a great deal of hope.
Short: Another disappointing season after showing so many signs in his debut year, with another batch of young players coming in it's hard to keep hope, but somehow I still have some
Reliable key defender but unlikely scoring will change
Had a massive season back after returning from injury to be one of the best key backs in the comp, but far better in real life than in SuperCoach
Small forward so scoring is limited, a bad hamstring injury in pre-season won't help either
Definition of a role player up forward for the Suns, and certainly not worried about scoring Fantasy points

Comment: Sheldrick is a contested ball winning bull who led the Under-19 Championships in contested possessions, so it was a surprise when Swans debuted him in Round 1 2022 as a small forward. He didn't play again at AFL level that season, but after a 158 AFL Fantasy points at VFL level, he featured in Round 7 last season for the first time since. He was subbed out on just 11 and went back to the VFL where he scored a 130 AFL Fantasy points. He played again at AFL level in Round 10 where he started sub and scored just 9, and also played VFL that week for a 118 AF. So while his career scores at AFL read 43, 11 and 9, he showed at the level below that he had something special. We then finally saw him get a decent run at AFL level, playing four games in a row at 87, despite playing just 64% TOG. He then did his syndesmosis in Round 17 on 53 and he didn't feature again. So on face value, he's priced at 55 (discount to his 60 average due to playing seven games) and he averaged 87 if you exclude his sub games and when he was injured and that was from just 64% TOG. The question is if he features in their starting midfield rotation now with Adams and Jordon arriving and Warner set for more time in there. If he does, then he might be the breakout candidate we're chasing and can make the 150k. We'll get an idea of role, TOG and scoring in the opening round, but I feel he might be a year away.
Short: Contested bull got his change mid-season and showed he's going to be a Fantasy stud of the future with an insane PPM, the question is if he gets midfield minutes this season
In and out of the side and a gun at lower levels but scoring will always be limited in his small forward role at the top level
A nice intercept defender when on, but scoring typical for a key defender

Comment: A classy, tall midfielder who was touted as a top 10 pick in 2021, but slipped to 21. He didn't play at AFL level in his first season, however played every game he was healthy for in 2023 in a sign how high Freo rate him. He was sub or subbed out on seven occasions, and even the games wasn't he only went over 70% TOG six times. So there is clear upside considering his 54 average game from 57% TOG. He'll eventually be an inside midfielder for Freo and from what he's shown he might be a pretty good one, but with Brayshaw, Serong and Young locked into the inside roles, it's hard to see Johnson increasing the 21% CBA figure he averaged last season, so I doubt we'll see the 30+ point bump we need from him to be a viable starting pick at that price and position. Update: Strong reports coming out of Freo on his development, I still find it hard to see him getting the CBA bump given the tight rotation, but he's got himself onto the watchlist.
Short: Looked good in his first season at the level and outside of his seven games where he was sub/subbed off he averaged 72, just not sure he'll get the inside time for a breakout this year

Comment: The former number three pick has always been on the radar due to his draft position, but is yet to deliver consistently at AFL level. His AFL Fantasy numbers at VFL level are getting better, averaging 75 in 2021, 97 in 2022 and then an impressive 111 in last season. He just hasn't had a proper crack at it at AFL level due to the midfield depth at Carlton. He played two matches in 2022 and 10 last year, but was sub for five of them. His PPM rate was pretty good and he averaged 85 when playing the full game. He's now at the Saints who have been trying to inject speed into their midfield for a few seasons now and I can see him getting regular minutes in there this season. Priced at 57 and MID-only, I think you'd want him averaging over 85, which he can do if the CBAs are over 50%. A pre-season watch, not for the first time, but he might have been worth the wait. Update: A pre-season hamstring injury may stall his Round 1 hopes.
Short: We've been waiting for a breakout and maybe a move to the Saints will unlock that
Hard running wing who might see more than the 10 games he played in 2023, but not a scorer
Defender picked up in the mid-season draft, averaged 76 in the VFL and won the VFL B&F, one to watch
Role player who has been great for Geelong after being picked up in the Rookie Draft, but not one for SuperCoach
Talented forward who played 22 games after moving to Geelong but scoring won't change much in this role
One of the best defenders in the comp and at just 24, he'll improve his reputation again in 2024, however he still won't be SuperCoach relevant, despite his elite intercept stats

Comment: The 22-year-old deserves some luck after two ACL injuries in two seasons. He's played as a small defender which hasn't been conducive to decent SuperCoach scoring, but he's also played as a rebounding half-back, and it's the latter that he's said to be earmarked for under Hardwick in 2024. This sparks some interest in him, but the early bye makes it tough. One to keep on the radar in case he does have a Jayden Short type role early in the ear.
Short: Coming off successive knee reconstructions he comes in cheap, has scored okay in the past but also played lockdown which makes it tough
After an interrupted start to his career, he's had a clean bill of health since moving to the Lions, however scoring hasn't changed in that time and nothing to say it will
An ACL injury will see him miss at least the first half of the season for the Lions
Moved back to the wing in 2023 where he's scored 70+ before, but was limited to around the 60 mark and that might be him from here
34-year-old key forward, not the combo you want
Now 30 and always seems to be on the fringe at the Swans
Picked back up in the mid-season draft as a running wing, didn't score well in his years at the Pies and nothing changed at the Dogs

Comment: The former top five pick moved to the Roos in the off-season in search for more opportunity, after averaging 11 games per season. He scored 111 in Round 1 last year, but failed to score over 80 until the Round 24. He did score well at VFL level though, averaging 110 AFL Fantasy points. He should be locked into a wing role at the Roos, but it's a role that lacks consistent scoring at AFL level so I'd keep expectations in check.
Short: A new team should help the former Pick 5 get more chances and scoring at VFL level is good (110 AFL Fantasy points), but likely to take a wing role at the Roos which will cap his output

Comment: Cunningham has a booming kick and after a 27% KI rate in the last five games of 2021, I thought he could take his game to the next level after Jordan Dawson left. However, Blakey ended up taking that slack and Cunningham hasn't taken a kick-in since. He played every game last season but was a mix between forward and back. I still have some hope he will improve his output, but not enough to be relevant.
Short: Played every game last year after being on the outer the year before, I was actually bullish on him but 0% KI the last two seasons shows he's more of a role player than a distributor
Back at the Hawks but I doubt he will return to his scoring when he was there
Small forward who is now at the Dees, however role and scoring will unlikely change
Small forward took a while to find his feet at Port, but even his 83 L5 average isn't nearly enough

Comment: Chapman has showed great signs in his first few seasons at AFL and certainly looks like one for the future. He was limited to just the three matches last year due to a shoulder injury which means he starts at a discounted price, and he's back fit and there's a bit of buzz coming out of Freo about him. He was always behind Young, Ryan and Clark for distribution in defence, but with Young moving to the midfield, he's moves up one spot on the pecking order. The other talk is that he will fill the wing role left by Henry, but it now seems Sharp will take that which is a good thing for Chapman's scoring. I wouldn't even be surprised if we see him spend some time inside. Regardless, he's easily beat his priced at figure, with lower estimates being 75+, and that would be enough for him to make the magic $150k figure. 10 Feb Update: Sent for scans after injuring his hamstring in the intra-club. It's his hamstrings that he's had issues with in the past. He had hamstring surgery last season and saw a specialist in Spain in the off-season, so it's a bit more concerning that a regular one. Unless news comes out that it's minor, it's time to find a replacement.
Short: Very impressive on limited exposure and heading into his 4th season, is poised to breakout but a pre-season hamstring injury is a big worry given his history
Great key position defender but won't score enough to be relevant
Had his best season yet as Buddy bowed out, but key forward scoring will always be limited
Became a regular last season and looks the goods, but limited to a forward role, not the defensive role he put up monster scores in the VFL
General defender with limited scoring
I thought we'd see more of him after a super impressive debut in 2022, but only played the 10 games for a rebuilding team so not a great sign
Shutdown small defender who was very highly rated prior to breaking a leg but found himself on the outer last season, regardless his scoring in that role will be limited

Comment: It's crazy that a player with a career high average of 124, multiple seasons over 120 is available with forward status priced at 51 and he's not a guaranteed good pick! Fyfe has been impacted by injuries in six of his last eight seasons, however hit rock bottom in the last two. He finished 2022 with an average of 63, which is 67 points off his best ever 124. He finished 2023 with an average of 51, which is 73 points off his best ever 124. The form drop is both injury related (4 games under 60% TOG in 2024) but also came about from the emergence of the young Freo midfield, meaning Fyfe has been playing more time forward. This time last season, Fyfe was earmarked for a full-time forward role, but that was changed after he struggled in the early rounds and he increased his CBAs as the season went on, before a season ending injury in Round 16. He's back training with the mids this season and while he's going to be behind Serong, Brayshaw and Young for CBA rotations, I see him staying at the 40% mark. I think he can push his scoring up to the 75-80 mark, which actually makes him an okay starting option, particularly if he can get a few 90+ scores early. However, his body, role and output has been too hard to trust in recent years, so there is a lot of risk in the pick.
Short: A SC hall of famer with forward status and priced less than half his career best average - but there are still doubts whether he's a good pick
A nice intercept marker, but a genuine full-back and not a player you want in your team
Mature age forward looked great in his two matches at AFL level last year and set for a regular role with the departure of Shultz, but the role is a small pressure forward so scoring will be limited
Was a regular 80+ scorer at the GC, but in the general forward role at the Blues he's been closer to the 60s and it's hard to see that changing without a role change
Key defender who got a bump in 2022 with McGovern out, averaging 105 post-bye, but likely back to the 80s now
Small forward who regress from his AA season of 77, as the Cats did, and might continue to find it tough while Cats aren't as strong
Key forward scoring isn't great but he'll unfortunately miss the season with an ACL anyway
Plays as a speedy small forward and certainly hasn't looked a scorer to date, spent some time in the midfield in H2 and training there over the pre-season but I doubt that will change things
Fell out of favour but hasn't shown much scoring even with CBAs
Managed just five matches last season and I think GWS might have moved passed him now

Comment: Not sure theres a harder player to get a read on than Jaidyn Stephenson, in real life and in Fantasy. He burst back into relevance in his first season at the Roos, which included going over 110 three times and 150 once while playing as a CBA midfielder. He then took a step back in 2022, but finished the season in the backline and while he was found out at times defensively, he provided some run and looked at his best, averaging 85 points in his last five with 28% kick-ins. However, Clarko put him back to the forward line last season and he managed the lowest average of his career. It sounds like Fisher and McKercher are going to take the half-back roles, and there is no room in the midfield now, so I imagine Stephenson will be used as a forward or wing in 2024, and while it's hard to see him not improving on 2023, I doubt it's going to be anything significant.
Short: As hard to read as any in the game, has had stretches where can could be a top 6, either in defence or inside mid, but played mostly forward under Clarko and that's going to limit his scoring

Comment: Zak Jones has progressed from a half-back flanker to a wingman to an inside midfielder, where he provided something different to the plethora of inside mids (Steele, Ross, Brad Crouch). He played the role pretty well in 2021, averaging 93 highlighted by a 153 and 123 in consecutive weeks. He hasn't hit those heights since though, averaging 64 and 56 from 13 and four games due to an Achilles issue and then a quad strain, after dealing with soft tissue issues in 2022. He played his first game in the VFL in Round 14 and then scored 127 AFL Fantasy points in his second VFL game. That saw him back in the 1s for the first time under Ross, and in the three full games he averaged 48% CBAs which is a great sign. However, an early knee injury finished his season in Round 20. He enters 2024 still less than 30 and priced at 45. He can surpass that by 30 points if he maintains that midfield role. There hasn't been much said of him this pre-season, but he's one I'm keeping an eye on.
Short: Two interrupted seasons after three seasons scoring over 86, if he can get back to full fitness and play a midfield role, he could prove a sleeper in 2024
Vandermeer has some talent, but scoring hasn't moved much from the 50-mark
Irishman showed some great signs with a booming kick and became a regular with 19 games in 2023, but doesn't look like he's going to be a scorer
Key defender who's career best was when he took 60% of the KIs, that won't happen again so he'll remain around the 50-mark

Comment: Thilthorpe has been a slow burn since being taken with Pick 2 of the 2020 draft. It was always going to be the case being a tall forward, but he's slowing increased his ruck time while giving ROB a chop out. There is talk that he might take over as the number one option in 2024, which would be a big call as while no star, ROB has been serviceable. But if it occurs, we might see a nice 20+ point bump to his scoring. I doubt it will be enough to be a worthwhile selection, but let's see how he goes in the pre-season matches.
Short: Been a slow burn but word is he might progress to the number one ruck this season, which would bring about a nice boost in scoring

Comment: Tsatas arrived at the Bombers with high hopes following over 33 disposals and seven marks a game throughout his NAB League campaign. A pre-season injury meant he wasn't available to start the season and then was forced to work hard for his spot, despite the Bombers' woes. He played seven VFL matches and had more than 30 touches in two of them. He came in for the final four games of the year and looked okay without being amazing, limited to a forward and wing role with little inside action (15% CBAs). Natural development and a full pre-season should set him up for a second year breakout, but the Bombers have so many who can run through the inside and I have Hobbs and Caldwell over him in the rotation, so we might see him having to bide his time in lesser roles. A watch for the pre-season given his forward status and ball winning ability, but I haven't got great hopes for him this season.
Short: A meniscus tear last pre-season saw highly touted topfive draftee have to wait until Round 21 for a debut and VFL and NAB League form suggest he'll be a scorer
Club change but still a key defender so scoring will unlikely change
Plays the defensive forward role super well for the Pies, just not a role for SuperCoach
Lockdown defender who looked at home in the AFL in his first season, not a scorer though
Ferocious key forward who applied a lot of pressure, now a regular for Freo but hard to see his scoring become relevant in this game
Changed club but won't be in a scoring role nor has he shown scoring ability

Comment: The 2022 draft is looking like a special one and the player taken at Pick 10 could end up as good as any. Phillipou has all the attributes of a modern day player - a big body, high leap, booming kick and a goal kicker. The only thing he didn't demonstrate in his debut season was accumulation, but he showcased that in his draft year where he averaged 123 AFL Fantasy points from eight games. He played a deep forward role in his first season, but got a taste of the midfield as the season went on - 5% CBAs pre-bye, 13% post and 20% in the L5. It's inevitable he ends up as a midfielder, but with no shortage of midfielders at the Saints at the moment, I doubt we'll see a significant jump this year.
Short: Massive numbers in his draft year and comparisons to Bont and Danger, played a deep forward role to start his career but a bump in CBAs to finish the season might be a sign of things to come
Shutdown defender who did his ACL last season and will miss a fair bit of 2024
Key utility who actually really impressed as a forward in 2023, but neither role is good for scoring
Just the seven matches last season with strangely three as sub proves he's there for ruck depth
A trade to the Hawks after just 15 seasons at the Dons, beautiful user and could play on a wing this season but I'm not sure he's much of an accumulator

Comment: Top 10 pick with monster junior numbers (109 AF average in WAFL Colts, three x 130+ in WAFL league), high endurance and good size. After just four games in his debut season (2 as sub), Erasmus played 14 matches last season. However, six of those he wore the vest, so he finished with 43 average from 51% TOG. His numbers at the lower level and PPM at AFL in his second season suggest he might be a scorer of the future. I think we'll see a lot more of him this season following the departures in the off-season, but it's still going to be hard to get consistent CBAs with Brayshaw, Serong, Young, Johnson, Fyfe and O'Meara taking up the majority. Expect a nice bump in average, but it might be a year or two before we see him putting up consistent numbers worthy of SuperCoach selection.
Short: Former top 10 pick got his chance last year but was used sparingly with six vests, but he's an accumulator at the lower level and should see more TOG this season following the departures

Comment: After nine games in three seasons, West finally got his chance in 2022 and carved out a nice role as a small pressure forward. However, that didn't last long and he was back out of the side for most of the first half of 2023. West was a highly touted inside midfielder as a junior, but with the depth of the midfield at the Dogs, he looks like he's going to continue in the forward role when in the side. While that's the case, he won't be a factor in SuperCoach.
Short: I though he found a spot as a small forward in 2022, but he continued to be in and out if the side in 2023 and I doubt we'll see him in a midfield role which is where he'd need to be to score
Emerging key forward who showed off his strong set of hands in his first season of playing AFL, has future star all over him and could even be a SuperCoach one, but not for a few years yet

Comment: A back up ruck to Draper who has impressed at reserves level. He won the VFL Best and Fairest for the Bombers in 2021 and increased his VFL Fantasy average from 87 to 116 last season, showing his potential. Draper has been the clear choice for number one ruck at Essendon, but he's had an interrupted pre-season so hopefully we see more of Bryan this year.
Short: Been third in line behind Draper and Phillips but VFL numbers are impressive so he hopefully gets his chance now Phillips has gone
Missed all of 2023 with a serious hamstring injury and now 32, he's not a great option in this game
Small forward who is a nice addition to West Coast's list, but in that role his scoring is going to be limited
Key defender who excels in one-on-ones but is surrounded by better ball users so won't get much possession

Comment: The big Humper is a fun watch. Hits the ball hard, skilful and gets the ball in the right spots. He's in the De Goey, Petracca, Dusty mold of a very dangerous forward of centre player. It's the role every football team wants but it's a very hard role to play, and it's certainly what we want in SuperCoach as that's where a lot of the scoring is. I think he'll continue to develop his fitness and craft in a 20/80 fwd/mid split, but he's only an injury or two away from that flipping the other way and he could be a factor in SuperCoach this season, but I'm keeping my expectations in check for the future star.
Short: Pick six of 2022 really impressed in his first season as a powerful fwd/mid which is a hard role to play but he's going to end up a very good one

Comment: There's no doubting Coleman-Jones has talent, however he's yet to really crack it at AFL level. Not even a move to the Kangaroos provided more job security, with just 19 games since arriving in 2022 at an average of 51. He continued to dominate at lower level, highlighted by a 167 AF score in R8 last year after averaging 104 and 115 at VFL level the two years prior. Those scores came from playing predominantly in the ruck and at AFL level, he plays as a key forward. If he's ever handed to keys to be the number one ruck then he could be worth a look, but that's an unlikely scenario. Maybe if Xerri goes down, which we certainly don't want!
Short: Yet to cement his spot even with the move to North, but Goldy out should open up some R2 opportunities
Just the five games last season (2 as sub) after seven in his debut season, SANFL AF average of 81 is encouraging and might get a chance with Duursma traded

Comment: Bonner has had flashes of good scores throughout his career, however he's never put together a full season. He should get more chances this season after a move to Saints in the off-season, but MID-only rules him out.
Short: Now at the Saints after showing flashes at Port, MID-only makes it hard but 104 AF SANFL average shows he can score if given a chance
Fringe player who hasn't scored over 70 in 13 seasons
Gun intercept defender better in real life than SuperCoach
Will only continue to grow in his role with Buddy now gone but won't score enough to be relevant

Comment: Schoenberg had slowly increased his midfield role, from 18% CBAs in 2020, 35% in 2021, 38% in the first half of 2022 and then 56% to finish. However, that dropped to 30% in 2023 as he found himself out of the Crows' best 22, playing 11 matches and sub for 3. Adelaide have drafted very well in recent times and the acquisitions of Pedler, Rachelle, Soligo and Rankine have provided a different dimension to the Crows, and with Dawson and Laird taking full-time midfield roles, I think Schoenberg will find himself on the outer again. 105 AF SANFL average is encouraging though, however he'll be spending the start of the season recovering from a ruptured Achilles.
Short: Recovering from a ruptured Achilles, however fell out of favour in 2023 with Soligo/Rachelle/Pedler/Rankine taking priority
Key position player who has struggled for games at multiple clubs, now a premiership player but I doubt his scoring will change
Medium forward who was trialled in defence in 2023, not sure what Dimmer has planned for him but I doubt it will result in a bump in scoring
Natural half-forward which Adelaide seem to have a lot of so he played in defence in 2023, SANFL average was okay without catching the eye
Small pressure forward who has been a regular the past two seasons but scoring is limited
Another club change but scoring hasn't been great in any role
Hard working half-forward but a role player for the Dons and might find opportunities limited again this season
Back playing most weeks after being in and out of the side in 2022, but playing in a far more defensive role than he did when he averaged 85
Played 18 matches after being overlooked in the draft and showed plenty, but a 20-year-old key forward so won't be relevant in this game

Comment: After seeing consistent midfield minutes in his debut season with 31% CBAs in the first half, Jordon took up a wing role in 2022 left vacant by Brayshaw moving to a half-back. He played an important role for the team, playing 22 games at an average of 75. However, the acquisition of Hunter on a wing pushed Jordon out and meant he spent time forward in a bit role, including being sub/subbed off seven times. Remove these sub 51% TOG games and he averaged 68, which is more in line with his first two seasons, however in a lesser role. He showed he's developed as a scorer though, averaging 120 AF in the VFL. While the Swans' midfield is getting pretty deep, they have lost Stephens on a wing and Mills for the front part of the season. I can see Jordon getting some minutes in the middle and if he does, he's more than capable of a 77+ average and higher if it's inside mid, which as a forward this year makes him a great pick. It's a good and bad thing that he plays Round 1, so we'll have a good look at his role and scoring, but at that price point he's one I'm okay starting with if he can go 77+, despite the Round 5 bye.
Short: Moved to the Swans after being kicked out of the midfield/wing rotation at the Dees where he showed signs in the last, fresh start with forward status could be just what he (and we!) are after

Impressed in his debut season with some (not me) saying he'll end up better than Ashcroft, but second season as a wing with MID-only status, he's not going to be that for at least this year unless he moves inside
Never been an accumulator of the football, illustrated by his best career season being 70 in 14 seasons
Forward status and new coach could bring a role change, but there's a bit going on there at the moment
Some massive scores in the VFL but played a shutdown role when at AFL level, which he didn't do a heap of in 2023
Small forward, better in real life than in SuperCoach, as showed by his impact in the finals series
Fringe defender who has never been an accumulator and unlikely to change
Small forward has showed plenty in his first two seasons, but that still led to a 50 average such is the role
Key defender in his 13th season and never been a scorer
Small forward who lost his spot in 2023 and even when he does play, he doesn't make an impact in this game
Defender without much attacking side to his game
Back-to-back injury impacted seasons and that 97 seasons seem a distant memory

Comment: The former pick 28 played seven games in his debut season and impressed with his kicking skills and speed. However, he only managed the three games at AFL level last season with Taranto and Hopper taking the midfield spots. In a developing side under a new coach, I expect to see a lot more of Sonsie in 2024 and while I doubt he'll have a big impact, he's worth monitoring with his forward status. 115 and 117 AF in back-to-back weeks at VFL level before suspension finished his season shows he does have the potential to score.
Short: Impressed in his debut season but the arrival of Taranto and Hopper meant he played just the three last season, highly touted and I think we'll see a lot more of him in 2024 will need time before being a regular midfielder
Former Pick 8 has had a disappointing career to date and fell out of favour last season managing just 12 games after 18+ the three prior, scoring has been limited throughout also
33-year-old small forward who scored well in the past with stints in the midfield, but those days are over now
Gun small defender, often takes the opposition's number one medium forward, not a role for producing decent scores
Solid defender but best season average is just 67
Mid-season pickup with some nice forward craft, West Coast might have found one here but a young key forward won't score much in this game
Has shown signs he'll be a gun IRL one day with his size and elite marking ability, but will need a few years before he's mature enough to make an impact in SuperCoach
Club change worked great for him in 2023 but the dashing defender has never been much of a scorer

Comment: Williams has been disappointing since his move to the Blues - for Carlton fans and Fantasy coaches. He was a popular mid-priced pick in 2021 following a change of clubs for more midfield time after averaging 108 in the second half of 2019 in a midfield role. After a string of poor performances, he was banished from the midfield and played in defence. That defence role continued before he badly injured his calf, missing the majority of the season. He then did his ACL in the 2023 pre-season and missed the entire year. He now enters 2024 priced at 39 which is about 40 less than what he can produce in a defensive role and 50 less in a midfield role. Regardless of role, he's significantly underpriced and one of the bargains of the season. The only issue is his Round 2 bye. How much will he have to score in Round 0 for you to pick him? I think 75+ will make it worthwhile, which I expect him to do.
Short: Due for a change of luck and as long as he's healthy, he'll prove one of the bargains of the season
Played 17 matches in his second season and showed clear talent with his intercept marking ability, will get better again but role isn't conducive to decent scoring
Moving to Richmond should see him become a regular in 2023, but key forward scoring won't change much
The veteran medium forward has been on the fringe of the Demons' 22 for a while now and when he does play it's as a role player

Comment: The Pick 7 of the 2022 National drat was one of the most hyped rookies leading into last season after he scored 99 in the pre-season match, second highest for the Hawks, from a juicy midfield role. And after 90 from 52% CBAs in R1, it look like he was going to be one of the rookies for the season. However, never went above 30% after that, and despite a 89 in R3, he quickly found himself out of the Hawks' best 22, playing as sub in R5 and dropped after R6. He then played as sub a further three times and played twice in the last eight rounds. His VFL numbers were encouraging in that time, averaging 93 AF for the season but had two scores 119+. He enters 2024 with forward status and with another pre-season under his belt, will be eying off a spot in the midfield. The issue is, a lot are at the Hawks. But if he happens to be the one to soak up the midfield minutes from Day, who might be missing the start of the season, or Worpel, who I can see missing out, then he might be worth jumping on. Like I've said before with second year breakouts, you can afford to wait a few weeks to see if his role and scoring is sustainable first.
Short: Solid debut season but after 99 in the pre-season match, I think we expected more, forward status makes him of interest in his second season though if he can recapture that form and role
22 games in 2023 as a small forward/wing, averaged sub-50 in his career to date and unless there's a role change, it's hard to see that changing

Recruited as a mature age running defender to fill the void of Heath Shaw retiring and Zac Williams' departure, but GWS have no shortage of those and he's spent most his time in the VFL or on a wing at AFL level
A tall (193cm) midfielder who has nice numbers in juniors and VFL, but been on the fringe at the Cats and there are a few ahead of him in the midfield mix

Mature-aged defender who arrived with some massive VFL AF scores and got his chance after 112 and 136 in R2 & R4, but played a more defensive role at AFL level meaning that scoring power didn't carry across - 50 average post-bye
Has put up some big numbers in the VFL, averaging 90+ the last three years, but yet to show it at AFL level
Promising key forward who has showed he'll become a very good player, but young key forwards are never good SuperCoach options
Key position defender and will be a star in the future but unfortunately he's better in real life than SuperCoach
Talented defender with elite intercept marking ability but plagued by injuries and his body is too hard to trust now
Multiple goals in six games, goalless in every other game (including seven straight!) is too inconsistent to consider
Big ball winner in the WAFL and as a junior but often in the defensive forward role at AFL level which just isn't a scoring option
Defensive-minded inside mid with high handballing numbers, played two matches in his debut season and scoring at VFL level suggests he'll need some time
Interrupted last two seasons, highly-rated but tough at that price and MID-only
Former steeplechaser is highly rated at the Lions, but their midfield has so many mouths to feed and it's hard to see Sharp breaking in
Tall, outside mid/winger with big numbers in his draft year and at VFL level, but yet to really show he can accumulate at the top
Returning from an ACL and hopefully we see the best of him as he showed some great signs early, but a young key forward role always see his scoring limited

Mobile ruck/key forward played 14 matches in 2023 after scoring -1 in his sole game beforehand, showed some great signs and will see more chances with Soldo on the move but I doubt he'll score much with Nank healthy
Heartbreakingly missing out on the Prelim and GF with an ankle injury, but a genuine key back and scoring is relatively capped
Big SANFL numbers for a number of years now, but still behind O'Brien and even Thilthorpe who looks next in line for the number one ruck role
Drafted as a mid but found his own in the small forward role at WC and looks like he's going to be a good one, not for SuperCoach though
Depth ruck with monster VFL numbers (112 average in 2022, 96 while coming back from injury in 2023) and Ross seemed pretty happy to ruck Marshall solo
Reliable defender but unless he somehow moves into a distribution role, there's little upside in his SuperCoach relevance

Comment: Hewett is the modern midfielder who breaks from stoppages and hits the scoreboard. While his numbers don't look great (55 AF average in his draft year, 46 in his 14 AFL matches and 26 AF in the WAFL last year), he's a much better player than that. In his draft year, he scored 115 AF when returning through the WAFL Reserves in 2022 and had a huge game one for WA in the U18 Champs where he picked up BOG honours, collecting 29 disposals and two goals. He then spent most of his year in the WAFL against tougher opposition, which is why his junior scores are lower than the other first rounders of the draft. He showed some great signs in his debut season in a limited role and TOG. He's dealing with a foot issue this pre-season, so I think it's going to be a slow build, but he might be a player of the future.
Short: Showed spark in his debut season and WC now have a few decent kids coming through, will be more forward than mid in the short term but should be a midfielder in time
Good on social media but fell out of the side in Round 5 and is yet to show much scoring ability
On the wrong side of 30 and key forward not a great combo
Debuted in 2023 and played every game as a shutdown defender, excelled in the role however scoring looks very limited

Thrown around in a few key positions but hasn't shown much on the scoring front since juniors

Played one game for 69 but averaging 65 and 68 in juniors and the VFL respectively doesn't read well
Looks great as a small forward, just not a SuperCoach scorer

Never managed more than six games in a season since being drafted, but should get his chance this season and there is positive noise coming from Richmond about his pre-season, scoring appears limited at VFL level though
Very consistent just the wrong type, scoring between 41 and 68 in all 10 of his full games
Strong bodied defender seems a favourite at Port and was even flagged for mid-time in the past, scoring at all levels is underwhelming though
Former Pick 6 played 14 matches in his first season for the Swans, displayed some of his intercept marking ability but not much else from a scoring perspective

Comment: Arrived as a mature age (26) SSP selection after being SANFL's premier key forward in recent years, averaging 128 AF in 2021. He didn't disappoint, scoring 127 on debut and I had to double take if it was him or Marshall. Unfortunately, he did his knee in Round 6 and missed the rest of the season. He then missed the majority of the 2023 season with a foot injury. Hopefully he gets a proper run at it this season and might eat into Marshall's scoring, but I doubt he's going to be relevant himself.
Short: Back from injury but will likely play back-up to Marshall
Former first rounder scored nicely at SANFL level but stuck as a small forward at AFL level and can't get away from the sub vest
Sharman has an impressive set of hands and played 16 matches last season after a handful the two prior, playing as a 3rd tall which makes it tricky for consistent scoring
Has managed to get his body right after frequent injury concerns earlier in his career, however genuine key defenders don't score well
Tough defender who I confuse with Moore at times such is his marking ability, but far from a scorer in SuperCoach
Great VFL average but not a scorer as a medium forward at AFL level
A move to the GC gave hope he could become a consistent scorer of the half-back, but scoring actually dropped from his time as the Saints where he averaged 84 in the L5 of 2022
Mid-season draftee from the SANFL is now a regular at the Dons in a small forward role, not a great role for SuperCoach though
Small forward role which limits his scoring
Picked up in the mid-season draft in 2022 but has only managed five games with an average below 60, will likely be a regular in 2024 with North's injuries down back but VFL numbers he's not a scorer

A career average below 60 is about expected for the Irishman in his defensive role
Yet to show much scoring even at SANFL level
Elite running capacity which allowed him to shut down some of the best runners in the AFL, but its not a role that leads to scoring

Comment: Sweet has played 11 matches in the past three seasons as a back-up ruck to one of the best in the comp. In that time, he's put up some massive AF scores in the VFL, including 125 in his last six matches of 2023. So when the trade was made which saw him move to Port, a team who lost their ruck (Lycett) last year, we all thought he'd be the perfect R2 for us this season. However, shortly after the move, Port also added Soldo who I think is the better ruck. The setup is still worth monitoring in the pre-season just in case they decide to go with Sweet, but with the other options out there (Gawn, Grundy, Xerri), Sweet has lost a lot of his appeal. Update: With Soldo only returning to training from a finger injury, it sounds like Sweet might start the season as Port's R1. With Gawn and Grundy having an early bye, I'd be prepared to pay up for Sweet as R3 if he's named solo in Round 1.
Short: Mature-aged ruckman who played back-up at the Dogs so a move to Port in the off-season gave hope until Soldo joined him shortly after, but Soldo pre-season injury could open the door
Crafty medium forward put some good numbers up in the WAFL but stuck forward at AFL level and won't get near the same output
Didn't skip a beat after missing 2022, averaged 79 post-bye with spoils and intercept marking a feature, hard to see him improving on that though so he's not an option this year
Former first rounder has had an interrupted start to his career but had his chance last season and didn't show much, will need time
The Cannon has become a better player now he's more focused on shutdown roles, unfortunately it means his scoring will be limited

Been on the outer the past four seasons after being a regular goal kicker for the Suns, word is he's training as a rebounding defender which could bring him into relevance, a watch in the pre-season games
Solid role in defence but it's not a scoring one

Versatile former high pick impressed everyone in his first season, playing 20 games, but limited to just 11 since, still not sure what role he'll play and while he's cheap, he hasnt shown he's a scorer
Small forward who managed 22 games in 2023 but very limited scoring at all levels
Had a solid season with 17 games but even the 52 he averaged excluding his five sub games isn't what we're after

Been waiting in the wings as a backup ruck and got his chance in 2023 when Witts was injury, faced a baptism of fire going up against Marshall and Darcy/Jackson in his two games, Dimmer might change things but Witts will likely continue as solo
Great SANFL numbers and showed he could score with a 94 first game back after the nasty concussion in Round 2, probably want some security in his spot first though but he has a nice mark-kick game

Key defender coming back from an ACL injury
Key forward has struggled to cement a spot to date, talk of him switching to defence where I doubt we'll see the scoring bump his brother got from the same move
Has some nice forward craft but just the single score over 60 from 13 games last season

Comment: The former top 10 pick did his ACL in 2022 and then struggled with soft tissue injuries on return, meaning he hasn't played a game for 24 months. However, he has attributes to be a good Fantasy defender, a neat kick and ability to generate marks. He finished 2020 averaging 80 in the last five games and that's about the mark I think he can produce at his best. He's obviously going to need some time to find his feet when he returns but gets a fresh start at the Dogs and is one I'd lock in if named in Round 1.
Short: Hasnt played for 24 months and coming off some shocking injuries, but has always had attributes to be a good Fantasy defender and a move to the Dogs will hopefully unleash that
Well on the outer with just one game in 2023, decent scorer at VFL level but will be stuck forward at AFL level
Fringe key position player with very limited scoring
Genuine role player who even played backup ruck at times in 2023, averaged in the 40-50 range his whole career indicates he's not a scorer
Small forward has improved his output in the state league but even with removing his sub-affected scores his scoring isn't great at AFL level
Rioli breaking out and Short moving back to defence saw the dashing defender regress in 2023, unless Yze really mixes it up, I doubt he makes an impact in 2024

Key defender and certainly not a scorer

Comment: Robertson was one of the most hyped rookies in Fantasy when he was drafted, following his elite scoring in his draft year; 113 AF average in the National Championships (ranked 1) and 120 average in WAFL colts (also ranked 1). He hasnt done a heap at AFL level in his first four seasons, and despite matching his career high 16 matches in 2023, he bottomed out with a 45 average. This was largely due to his four games as sub and when in the team, he spent a lot of time forward. His 114 AF points in the VFL shows he still has it and improved from 104 the year prior. Dunkley and Ashcroft took his midfield minutes last year but with no Ashcroft, could we see DevRob injected back in the middle? I doubt it but he's always worth tracking due to his elite scoring at the lower level. Underwent surgery after playing in the Lions' Grand Final loss with a broken wrist and has had an interrupted pre-season.
Short: Junior gun who has displayed that same level of ball winning ability in the VFL, but limited to a forward or defensive role when at AFL level where his scoring has been limited, worth tracking if the CBAs ever come
Had some good scoring at VFL level but need some role certainty as his only game in 2023 was in the vest
The son-of does some nice things in defence but only eight games averaging less than 40 in his career to date
Snuck in for the PF and GF but he's on the fringe and has never scored well

Comment: Finlay is developing well in the VFL in a very hard team to break into. There was no under-age football in his draft year, so we had to rely on his 2019 year where he played as a 17-year-old for Oakleigh Chargers, a team that boasted Matt Rowell, Noah Anderson and Will Phillips in the midfield. Finlay was forced to play mostly across half-forward but showed some great signs and from all reports was more advanced than his (half) brother who by contrast only came good during the second half of his draft year. We saw the similarities in Finlay's debut when he was thrown into the middle for the final quarter and racked up over 10 disposals. He also managed 39 from just 37% TOG when used in the middle in his one game last season when sub. Hes averaged over 90 AF in the VFL since drafted, so the talent is there. Priced at 28 and with forward status, I think hes worth considering if hes named Round 1 as an expensive rookie but with more experience.
Short: Brother-of who has averaged over 90 AF in the VFL since being drafted, worth spending the extra cash if he gets his chance
Was recruited as a hard-running midfielder, but been used as a small forward when at AFL level and opportunity and scoring been limited

Comment: Hore returns to the AFL four years after being delisted. He was handy enough at AFL level, including a lowest score of 75 from Round 2 to Round 14 in 2019. He's added to his game in the VFL where he's averaged over 100 AF the past two seasons, compared to the 87 he went at in his initial draft year. Last season's average included seven scores over 120, thanks to a very high kick-to-handball ratio, highlighted by 31 kicks and one handball in his final game of the year. Rivers has been talked to be making a midfield move which could open up a spot for Hore in defence. We'll get a good look in the opening round, but he's one that if named in Round 1, he should be a worthwhile selection despite the early bye.
Short: Second chance at the Dees after being a mature-age draftee previously, averaged 71 back then but VFL form been prolific (over 30 kicks(!) in two of his last five games)
I didn't have the fringe key defender playing on a wing in 2024 on my bingo card, but that's where he's been training, might lead to a boost in scoring but I doubt it will be sustainable

Decent in the VFL but played a small forward role in his four games in 2023, one to watch as the Dees have some midfield spots to fill

Comment: Sharp has landed at Freo after being delisted by the Suns last season. It was a quick downfall considering he was a highly rated junior and showed great signs in 2021. He averaged 118 AF in the WAFL under 18s in his draft year and saw plenty of league action that season. It took a while to get his chance at AFL level, but in his second season he played the last nine matches for an average of 73 (excluding his sub game). Despite this, he was in and out of the side in 2022, never playing more than four games in a row. But in that time, he averaged 112 AF in the VFL. He didn't play a single AFL game in 2023, and while his VFL average was lower than 2022, he still managed two x 140+ games. Freo picked him up as a SSP and he's been dominating their running all pre-season. There are some flaws in his game so his job security will always be shaky, but there's a wing spot available and if named in Round 1, he should prove a worthy selection.
Short: Elite runner with a second chance at Freo where he could take Henry's wing spot, averaged over 100 AF at VFL level since being drafted and at rookie price, can prove great value
A ruck project now further back with Port's acquisition of Soldo and Sweet

Comment: Port Adelaide worked hard to secure the rebounding defender, trading up first during the trade period before trading up on draft day. He backed this up by playing early, debuting in Round 2, however his debut season was hampered by a groin injury and didn't add to his one game. He featured three times in his second season. but sub for two of them and then hamstring surgery finished his season early. If he's named Round 1, defender rookies are scarce, and he comes with good credentials so he's worth watching.
Short: Former Pick 12 sounded like he was going to play early but groin issues halted his first season and a bad hamstring his second, highly rated so hopefully he gets a good run at it this season

Wore the vest in three of his six games in 2023, medium forward role but scoring at VFL level was good enough and he's creating a bit of buzz this pre-season out of the Lions, worth considering if named

Promising tall defender who was taken at Pick 9 in 2021, missed the entire 2023 season with injury and will hopefully bounce back, will make the 150k if he matches he average in his debut season which he should

Former top 10 pick where some thought he was as talented as any, has taken a lot of time to develop and had some injury issues, hopefully gets a nice run at it this season but developing key back his scoring will be limited

Key defender with a very modest scoring history at all levels

Comment: Drawing strong comparisons to Joel Selwood in his draft year, Clark is a strong inside mid with clean disposal and widely valued leadership traits. He was the second highest averaging player during the U18 Champs, going at 105 AF points per game and earning himself the Vic Country MVP. he also averaged 119 AF in his last four NAB league games of the season. So when he made his debut as sub in Round 9, it was highly anticipated. He didn't disappoint, laying five tackles and getting six touches in just over a quarter. However, a foot injury forced him to miss the rest of the season. Cats need to inject some youth in there, so we should see a lot more of him in 2024, hopefully without the sub vest on.
Short: Pick eight from 2022 draft didn't play after his debut (where he had five tackles in 25% TOG coming on as sub) due to a foot issue, he's healthy now and Cats need to inject some youth in there, so we should see a lot more of him in 2024
Irishman who has speed but modest scoring at VFL and AFL level

Comment: Dowling turned out a monster year in the SANFL U18s, filling the stat sheet with nearly 31 disposals, seven marks and five tackles a game on top of kicking 18.15 in front of goal. His standout performance and easily the standout performance of the draft, was his R16 match where he amassed 44 disposals including 35 kicks, to go with 17 marks, six tackles and 4.3 culminating in a 215 AF point display. He didn't play a game last season, however he showed his scoring capability in the SANFL with three games 108+ AF. They now have a lot of players in his type (fwd/mids), so he might have to wait his time. But if he ever gets his chance, keep an eye on him.
Short: Massive accumulator in his draft year - the highest Fantasy averaging player in the draft which included a 215 game - but played a forward role at SANFL level where he scored okay (3 x 108+ scores) but appears to be down the pecking order
Small forward who got exposure in his first season with four games, but might find it hard this season as the Roos have more depth

Comment: Binns was drafted as at pick 32 of the 2022 draft where he averaged 26 disposals and six marks a game in the National championships. However, he took that ball winning ability to another level in the VFL last season, averaging 116 per AF game, including 13 scores over 110+. The Carlton midfield runs as deep as any, but if he happens to be named, he's worth jumping on knowing what he's capable of against the bigger bodies.
Short: Amazing scoring in his first season at VFL level, averaged 116 AF with 13 110+, hopefully he gets his chance this season because he's a natural scorer
