Impact forward whose scoring at VFL level is very limited
Averaged 72 in WAFL League in his draft year, including 31 touches and seven tackles in the final round, so was surprised to see a 46 average in his first season at VFL level
Cat-B rook but one with scoring pedigree, averaged 96 at NAB League and 85 last season at VFL level, saw one game and might see more in 2023 with Cats rebuilding
Small forward scoring is limited
19-year-old tall forward who is going to need time to develop judging by his 39 average in the SANFL
Pressure forward, not the best role for scoring
Key defender with poor average at lower levels so doubt his scoring will be great
Medium defender with modest scoring at junior level and in the SANFL
West Coast Cat-B rookie with an underwhelming scoring history
204cm ruck will need a lot of time
Decent VFL numbers for a key forward
20-year-old ruck with modest scoring at VFL level, but with Grundy gone, he might be the back-up if anything ever happens to Max
Strong key back (100kgs and 197cm), but averaged under 40 in the VFL over the last two seasons
Rookie with senior experience, VFL average promising enough
Developing key forward, will need time
Small midfielder with great junior scores, modest SANFL scores though

Comment: This year's Pick 1 is ready-made for the top level, dominating the U18 Champs with his size and strength, averaging 20 disposals and a goal per game for a 99 AF point average. Highly touted from years out, he played underage in the Coates Talent League, remarkably featuring across three seasons and averaging 82 AF points from 18.5 disposals and two goals per game. He's a contested beast which should see him with even more upside in SuperCoach. Provided he's fit Round 1, he'll play and should be an automatic selection in our SuperCoach sides.
Short: The much-hyped number one pick will spend time between the midfield and defence in his first season and from all reports, will live up to the hype

Comment: The highest scoring draftee in this crop, McKercher should have no problems finding a place in North's young side. He put up huge numbers in the U18 Champs, averaging 32.5 disposals and six marks for an AF average of 131 across his four games. His Coates Talent League numbers were also great, managing to hit the scoreboard frequently for 12 goals from nine games and averaging 29.4 disposals and 112 AF points. Set to take the Sheezel-role in his first season, easing into things from a half back flank, and there's a chance he can match Sheezel's output year one.
Short: The highest scoring player in the draft and set to take the Sheezel-role in his first season down back - tick!

Comment: A big, imposing key forward, Walter comes in at 194cm and 97kg, dominating the Coates Talent League with 18 goals from his four games and spearheading the Allies' forward line to a maiden U18 Champs title. He's an interesting one for SuperCoach as he'll probably be quite a slow burn if young key forwards of the past are of any indication.
Short: A young key forward in the Curnow-mold, will need some time given his role and injury in the pre-season

Comment: A medium forward who can push through the midfield at times, Duursma kicked 33 goals in 12 games in the Coates Talent League to go with a 19.3 disposal average for 98 AF points. He trained with the Demons during the 2023 pre-season and featured in two games for Casey throughout the year. He's a natural scorer and should see plenty of opportunity at North.
Short: Excitement machine up forward and should have strong job security

Comment: A lethal small forward who produced an outstanding campaign in the U18 Champs, Watson's incredible goal sense brought him 14 goals in four games for Vic Metro. He showed his versatility at Coates Talent League level, switching to a distributing half-back role, averaging 80 AF points from 20 disposals per game. He could use some improvement in his stats across the board though, averaging just one tackle per game in the U18 Champs, increasing slightly to 2.1 in the Coates Talent League. Coming in at just 68kg, his scoring as a small forward will probably be capped, but could his final Coates Talent League season show enough to see him land a more scoring friendly role across half-back?
Short: Small forward who needs goals to score his points

Comment: Sanders is a primarily inside mid who racks up huge numbers, being voted the best player of the U18 Champs after amassing a 138 AF point average from 35.5 disposals and 6.3 marks per game. In the Coates Talent League he also averaged 30.6 disposals. He comes in well-developed and creating a lot of buzz at the Dogs, it's sounding like he's going to have an inside mid role from Round 1.
Short: Accumulating inside mid who could they're calling 'mini-Libba' at the Dogs, it's sounding like he's going to have an inside mid role from Round 1

Comment: An outside runner through the midfield, Windsor is best used hitting targets forward of centre. Though he averaged 78 in the Coates Talent League, we should assume his SuperCoach scoring may be a touch lower than his Fantasy output. In the U18 Champs he barely passed a 25% contested possession rate and though his disposal is efficient (went at 75% in the U18 Champs), it will struggle to bring his scoring up enough as with most other wingmen. It'll be interesting to see where he winds up positionally at Melbourne, given Langdon and Hunter were #1 and #2 respectively for TOG% for midfielders in 2023 and seemingly have both wing spots locked up. But in some vision released by the Dees in match-sim, he looks a player!
Short: Outside runner with a great K:H ratio and disposal efficiency, but a low contested possession rate will hurt his SC

Comment: Primarily a KPP at centre half-back, Curtin produced a huge U18 Champs campaign, averaging 23.5 disposals and 6.5 marks per game for a 104 AF point average and CHB honours in the Team of the Year. He featured heavily in the back half of the season in the WAFL, holding his own with 16.5 disposals and four marks per game, while he also played through the midfield at Colts level. Given his senior experience, he seems absolutely ready to make an impact at the top level.
Short: Well-built and versatile defender who can also push up the ground, should find somewhere to slot in for a Round 1 debut

Comment: The first ruck taken in this years draft, Read gets around the ground like a midfielder, racking up marks and disposals to go along with his hitouts. He went at 103 and 99 in the U18 Champs and Coates Talent League respectively, which included an average of over 20 disposals and six marks per game. His hitout-to-advantage rate is SuperCoach gold, with over 40% of his hitouts at Coates Talent League level going to advantage. At just 13 hitouts per game in the U18 Champs, he'll clearly need some time to develop before hitting the top level, but I'm very excited to see what he'll produce in the coming years.
Short: Ruck with incredible running power, will need some time to develop but he has the tools to be something very special one day

Comment: Caddy is a big key forward with a strong marking game who can also get his hands on the ball a bit. At Coates Talent League level he kicked 25 goals in nine appearances, averaging 16.3 disposals and 6.2 marks per game for 84 AF points. He also had a game with Carlton's VFL side, kicking 2.1 from eight disposals. Has been labelled a 'bolter' for Round 1, so will be interesting to see how he fares in selection early, but he'll likely be a slow burn anyway.
Short: Key forward with a lot of x-factor, already making an impact at training but given his age and position he will likely need time to develop

Comment: Boasting a great running capacity, O'Sullivan should fit into the mould of the high TOG full-backs, taking part in kick-mark chains and popping up for intercepts. The Cats are usually reluctant to give games to even their best rookies, so we should temper expectations on how often he'll feature this season.
Short: KPP at the Cats who will likely need some time to develop

Comment: The bolter of the 2023 draft, a pressure forward with unremarkable junior numbers
Short: The bolter of the 2023 draft, a pressure forward with unremarkable junior numbers

Comment: After performing strongly at Colts level in the WAFL in 2022, Tholstrup played 10 of his 11 games at League level in 2023, including featuring for WA in the U18 Champs in both seasons. While he lacks some consistency, he is an X-factor player, able to turn games in short periods, whether that is up forward or a brief stint in the middle. He averaged 86 AF points from 18.3 disposals and six marks for WA, though that fell to 55 against the bigger bodies in the WAFL indicating he'll need a bit of time to develop.
Short: X-factor up forward with brief stints in the middle

Comment: The Suns' third matched pick, Rogers is a great decision maker, able to use his agility to get in-and-under packs and accelerate out through packs to hit targets forward of centre. At AFL level it's unlikely we'll see him feature too often through the midfield as his 170cm frame will likely see him move to a small forward role like many other shorter onballers. Rogers has a natural scoring game, averaging nearly 24 disposals and six tackles across his turnouts for the Allies and Suns Academy, thus should be a viable pick if he is selected.
Short: Small midfielder, will likely be played as a pressure forward

Comment: Taken as a Father-Son pick, Croft is a 200cm key forward who averaged two goals per game in the Coates Talent League, also chopping out in the ruck on occasion. He averaged 61 and 55 in the Coates Talent League and U18 Champs respectively, which you'd expect to pick up naturally as a key forward, but he'll also join the queue of tall forwards at the Dogs, so don't expect him to feature too often, if at all, this season.
Short: Drafted to the Dogs as a key forward, will likely need time to develop

Comment: A more classical ruckman, Green averaged 24.3 hitouts in the U18 Champs though just 11.3 disposals. He'll need plenty of time to develop and given the Swans just traded in Grundy, we won't be seeing him too early.
Short: Young ruck who will need time to develop

Comment: The ultimate utility, Leake demonstrated to recruiters he could play in any position across his draft year with standout performances in both the U18 Champs and the Coates Talent League. Across half-back for the Allies and the Devils, he averaged nearly 17 disposals and five marks per game, but his versatility was best shown when pushing forward in the second half of the Coates Talent League season, with 15 goals in his last five games. Could be a chance at Round 1 if he builds up some strength in his first pre-season.
Short: Highly capable utility in any position on the ground

Comment: Possessing one of the highest ceilings of the draft, Wilson is a dangerous mid-forward, able to rack up disposals and make teams pay by hitting the scoreboard. He averaged 25.4 disposals and 5.8 marks per game in the Coates Talent League for an average of 104, also kicking 16 goals in 11 games and scoring 120+ four times. He's a natural scorer so if he plays we should look to find a spot for him on-field.
Short: High-scoring mid-forward with one of the highest ceilings of the draft

Comment: A key defender, it'll be interesting to see the type of role McCabe plays at the top level, having played more defensively in the U18 Champs compared to his SANFL U18 campaign. He averaged just 44 from an 11 disposal average for SA which jumped to an 82 average and 22 disposals for Central District. Having been well beaten by some of the key forwards at the U18 Champs, he'll need a big pre-season if he wants to play early in 2024.
Short: Has the size of a key defender but plays like a rebounding defender

Comment: Goad is a dynamic ruckman, performing strongly in the sprint and agility testing at the National Combine which had previously helped him to play basketball at a high level. He put up strong hitout numbers in the SANFL U18s, never going below 17 after Round 2, though he took a bit to get going with disposals, failing to reach double digits until Round six before passing the mark in five of his last 6. He'll be just a depth and development player at the moment as Xerri will look to get some consistency as North's first ruck.
Short: A young ruck who developed strongly over his draft year but will need more for the top level

Comment: While his numbers upfront don't appear that great, Edwards' year in the Coates Talent League was a tale of two halves, averaging just 47 until Round 12 as a defender, then exploding afterward with an 85 average with a move into the midfield. In that second half he averaged 23 disposals and a goal per game and showed ceilings in other stat lines, with an eight mark game and getting six tackles twice. He should complement the Adelaide midfield nicely, providing a AF point of difference as a more attacking option, however keep in mind he wasn't picked for the U18 Champs, so we'll see over the pre-season where he winds up in the pecking order.
Short: Big-bodied midfielder who can constantly hit the scoreboard

Comment: Having played in all three 'tall' roles over the season, Dawson performed best as a key defender in the back half of the season, featuring for Vic Country and Gippsland Power. Unfortunately his scoring goes nowhere as a back though, averaging just 24 AF points and totalling 19 disposals from his four games in the U18 Champs. At 200cm and just 86kg, he'll need plenty of time to pick some size up, and even then he's probably not a viable pick for us if past scoring is any indication.
Short: Tall utility who will need some time to develop

Comment: Though he was a bit quieter at League and Reserve levels, Hardeman dominated the WAFL Colts over the last two seasons as a midfielder, averaging 24 disposals with a handy 2:1 kick-to-handball ratio. In terms of scoring, he could do with a bit more of a ceiling across the stat lines, with just two games over four marks in the last two seasons and one game over six tackles in that same period. His natural position is as a running defender where he featured for WA and the AFL Academy, and if Sheezel moves in for more mid time, there could be an opening off half-back for North this season.
Short: Rebounding defender with a nice K:H ratio

Comment: Another Academy product for the Swans, Cleary is a tough inside midfielder who produced a strong campaign for the championship-winning Allies culminating in an All-Australian selection. He put strong numbers up across the lines, averaging 29 disposals, five marks, and six tackles for a 107 average. He has had some experience against the bigger bodies, having played six games for the Swans VFL side, where he averaged 18 disposals and 62 AF points. The Swans aren't exactly short of young mids, but they seem to rate Cleary very highly so keep an eye on him as the season comes closer.
Short: Tough inside mid with senior experience

Comment: An X-Factor midfielder, DeMattia doesn't rack up disposals consistently like some others, however he makes up for it with dangerous disposal going forward and keeps himself involved racking up tackles in the contest. He played multiple positions across his draft year proving his versatility, however even that might not be enough to find a spot early on in a mostly unchanged Pies list fresh off a flag.
Short: Highly sought after for his leadership qualities, can play across many positions

Comment: Yet another Academy product for the Suns this draft, Graham had a strong season as a midfielder before swapping into a half-back role for the Allies in the U18 Champs. He put up fantastic numbers at the Combine, placing second for the 20m sprint and 3rd in vertical and standing jumps. Given his development through the midfield, he should be able to score nicely if he manages to snag a spot on the half-back line this season.
Short: Transitioned to half-back after playing as a midfielder as a junior

Comment: A damaging rebound defender, Ryan produced great numbers in the Coates Talent League, averaging 22 disposals, five marks, and four tackles for 84 AF points. His output in the U18 Champs was diminished as he had to share the backline with a few other rebounding defenders for Vic Country. He'll likely need some time to develop to get comfortable at the top level. Bit of buzz coming out of Adelaide about him.
Short: Rebound defender with solid scoring, though his output dropped in the U18 Champs

Comment: Lethal in and around goals, Collard dominated the WAFL Colts, kicking 32 goals in 11 games, with four bags of 5, including both finals. He struggled in the U18 Champs though, totalling just nine disposals and two goals from his three games. In a positive for his scoring, he'll use nearly any excuse to kick rather than handball, going at nearly a 6:1 kick-to-handball ratio across the season (he handballed more than once just three times!). Drafted at just 65kg, combined with his apparent struggles for WA, he'll need plenty of time to strengthen his body before selection.
Short: Kicked 32 goals in 11 games in the Coates Talent League but struggled in U18 Champs

Comment: Able to kick long on both feet, Moir can be dangerous anywhere inside 50, best showcased by his 43 goals in 16 games across the last two seasons in the SANFL U18s. He also featured for SA in the U18 Champs for the last two seasons, though he struggled with form and injury interruptions during 2023. He also broke through for some games at Reserve level, kicking 4.3 in his first outing but was kept quiet with three goals in his other four games. Size-wise he should be almost ready to play Round 1, though he might need to up his consistency.
Short: Very highly rated medium forward though struggled with form and injury in 2023

Comment: A tall forward, Reid had an inconsistent season, invisible in some games to dominating others. He chopped out in the ruck and displayed good follow-up work around the ball, also showing good forward craft on the lead and in contests. Being a key forward, don't expect too much from him scoring-wise early in his career.
Short: Developing key forward who can chop out in the ruck

Comment: Morris is a tall forward able to hit the scoreboard from limited possessions. He kicked 30 goals in 10 games this season in the Coates Talent League, averaging 72 AF points from 11.7 disposals and 4.8 marks per game. Wait and see for the pre-season for how highly the Lions rate him but seems a very tough forward line to force his way in.
Short: Junior scoring mostly held up by goals, will be tough to break in early at the Lions

Comment: Having dominated the WAFL Colts early in the season with a remarkable 140 hitouts in four games, Edwards was promoted to WAFL Reserve level, performing solidly in the ruck with a 16 hitout, nine disposal average. He played in the previous two editions of the U18 Champs for WA, averaging 21 hitouts, 11 disposals and 62 AF points. Geelong have shown in the past they're more likely to develop rookies, while also happy enough with a serviceable ruckman so wouldn't expect much this season.
Short: Young ruck drafted by Geelong, will need some time to develop

Comment: Another of the rebounding defenders from Vic Country, Hastie's numbers took a dip at U18 Champs level after a strong output in the Coates Talent League. He averaged 20 disposals and five marks for 75 AF points for the Falcons, though only managing 12.5 disposals and 2.5 marks for a 49 average at the carnival. Being medium-sized, he's able to play both tall and small which might open more opportunities to play, though scoring will be limited.
Short: Rebounding defender with solid Coates Talent League numbers but diminished impact at U18 Champs

Comment: A small defender strong on the rebound, Wilson had a strong season in the Coates Talent League, averaging 23 disposals and four marks for 82 AF points. Another part of the Vic Country backline, his numbers dipped at the U18 Champs, averaging just 12 disposals, 1.5 marks and one tackle for 44 AF points. Blues don't mind giving games to their rookies but hard to see him breaking in for Round 1.
Short: Another rebounding defender with solid Coates Talent League numbers but diminished impact at U18 Champs

Comment: A hard-running winger, O'Driscoll showed his athletic prowess at the draft, placing top-10 in all tests, including first in the 20m sprint. While his 2022 numbers were better, he still put up a strong 2023 in the WAFL Colts, averaging 16 disposals and three marks for a 63 average. At the U18 Champs he averaged 12 disposals and six marks for 57 AF points, though showed a strong ceiling with a 19 disposal, 12 mark effort against SA. With quite a light frame, he'll probably need to put on some size over the pre-season to be considered.
Short: Ultra-athletic wingman who provides strong attack going inside 50

Comment: Roberts is a rebounding defender who averaged nearly identical numbers at both Coates Talent League and U18 Champs level, with 21 disposals and four marks in both for averages of 77 and 78 respectively. He earned All-Australian honours for his performance with Vic Metro and was very highly rated coming in to the draft, though surprisingly slipped after he was tipped as a possible first rounder. Should be a solid scorer and has ability to play either off half-back or across the wings if selected.
Short: Rebounding defender who kept solid scoring when stepping up a level

Comment: Initially tipped as a potential first-rounder, Schoenmaker faced a massive slide after falling out of favour with recruiters when an off-field indiscretion saw him face a 10-week ban at Coates Talent League level. He returned with a bang, dominating off half-back, averaging 27 disposals and six marks for 104 AF points. With an eye-watering 7:1 kick-to-handball ratio, he managed enough favour to feature in two games for the Allies, amassing 32 disposals and 15 marks for an 81 average. He played senior footy during his ban and could be a chance early if he impresses in the pre-season.
Short: The slider of the draft, a strong scorer off half-back with a lovely kick, sounds like he might need some time developing though

Comment: Ryan is a medium defender who can play both tall and small, and was named BOG for SA's final two games at the U18 Champs. He had a consistent year at SANFL U18 level, recording 17+ disposals in 11 of his 12 games and averaging 74 AF points with a ceiling of 101. His form was rewarded with turnouts for the SF and GF at Reserve level, winning both, though scoring was minimal, averaging seven disposals and two marks for 25 AF points.
Short: Medium defender with versatility to play tall and small

Comment: Though he could use some consistency with his numbers around the ground, excluding Round 1, Dear managed to register at least two scoring shots in every game this season in the Coates Talent League. His accuracy was not always there though, kicking 21.24 from 15 games, and seemingly when he's off, he can be really off, recording five games with scores of 42 or lower. Unlikely to play and there should be better scoring options anyway.
Short: Inconsistent key forward, likely a development pick

Comment: After a strong 2022 in his underage year playing in the WAFL Colts, Hall jumped straight to League level, remarkably increasing his numbers, finishing with a 19 disposal, three tackle average as well as managing one scoring shot per game. He dominated the U18 Champs for WA, averaging 27 disposals and 108 AF points playing through the midfield. Given his experience in the WAFL, you'd expect he'd be ready to play Round 1 so keep an eye on him during the pre-season.
Short: Inside mid with senior experience after dominating at lower levels

Comment: The first basement price rookie available, Simpson is a mid-forward who averaged 21.5 disposals and four marks for 86 AF points, also kicking seven goals across eight games. He played one game for Casey in the VFL early in the year, though he missed a decent chunk of the year after sustaining a corked thigh in his first game at the U18 Champs. There's an open spot on the wing at the Dockers after Henry's departure, could Simpson produce a strong enough pre-season to throw his hat in the ring?
Short: Mid-forward with experience in multiple midfield and forward half roles

Comment: A big-bodied inside mid already possessing the size and strength to play at the top level, Stevens averaged 29 disposals and five tackles for a 99 average in the Coates Talent League, including a monster 44 disposal effort in Round 11 for 148 AF points which could have been even bigger had he kicked more accurately than 0.3. He also showed flexibility to play off half-back as a distributor, even earning a spot there in the Talent League Team of the Year. Keep an eye out for him this season as he's shown he can score well anywhere and physically should be ready.
Short: Great junior scorer as an inside mid and some flexibility to half-back

Comment: Johnston is an X-factor midfielder able to push forward when required, earning himself two matches in the VFL after strong Coates Talent League form across the year. His ceiling performance came for Vic Metro with 29 disposals, five tackles and a goal, though his numbers fell after, averaging 15 disposals and 59 AF points from his four games. His scoring may not be great overall as he is generally an impact player rather than an accumulator.
Short: Impact player through the midfield and occasionally forward

Comment: Playing across multiple teams and positions, Thomas averaged 21 disposals, five tackles, and four marks for a 96 average in the Coates Talent League, managing eight goals from six games. He showed his wares as a midfielder early for the Giants Academy, amassing 30 disposals and 17 tackles in Round 1 for 158 before showing his forward craft for Oakleigh with 4.1 and 21 disposals for 105 in Round 17. Given his size, it's likely he'll see far more time as a forward than mid at the top level.
Short: Played in all thirds of the ground this season, showing scoring potential in each

Comment: Another player dangerous as both a mid and a forward, Garcia kicked eight goals in his first five games in the Coates Talent League with a 16 disposal average before pushing into the midfield and averaging 24 disposals over his next 5. Across the season he averaged nearly 20 disposals and seven tackles for 90 AF points, also kicking 13.3 from 11 games. Probably unlikely to play but could score well if given an opportunity.
Short: Loves to tackle and can flex between mid and forward

Comment: A small forward, Delean was rewarded for strong form in the SANFL U18s, playing three games late in the season at League level after kicking 38 goals in 13 games, managing 0 goalless games and a high of 7.2. AF point scoring was minimal otherwise however, averaging 67 in SANFL U18s, 52 at League level, and just 36 for SA at the U18 Champs. Should be better options elsewhere even if selected.
Short: Minimal scoring outside of kicking goals

Comment: Having played wing previously, Fonti bolted into draft contention after moving to the backline in 2023. He averaged 17 disposals and five marks in the WAFL Colts for a 67 average, dropping slightly across the board for a 54 average at the U18 Champs. The Giants are currently flush with distributing options off half-back, but they're excited about Fonti's versatility so maybe he could sneak in elsewhere.
Short: Medium defender with some dash off half-back

Comment: In typical wingman style, Freijah produced varying performances this season with three games under 60 to go along with a monster 152 which included six goals from 26 disposals and seven marks. He averaged 20 disposals and four marks for an 80 average and earned a wing spot for the Coates Talent League's Team of the Year.
Short: Winger with a ceiling but also some inconsistency

Comment: Dominated the SANFL U18s with 27 disposals, five marks, and six tackles for 110 AF points, earning a promotion to Reserve level where he kept displaying strong numbers across the stat lines and retaining an 83 AF point average from seven games. Given these strong performances against senior bodies, he should be ready to play early on if required, though he might be behind a few others as a mid at the Tigers.
Short: Big-bodied mid with a strong scoring profile

Comment: Port's second small forward pick in short succession after Anastasopolous, Charleson played primarily midfield before moving forward late in the season with great success. He kicked 17 goals in his last five games in the Coates Talent League, including a monster 8.4 to go with 22 disposals in Round 16 for 126. However, his numbers as a forward were sporadic, twice recording nine disposals after having previously fallen below 18 just once. If his U18 Champs numbers are anything to go by, he may need some development to earn a debut.
Short: Solid in the midfield but flourished when moving forward later in the season

Comment: After improving his output at WAFL Reserve level from 15 disposals to 23, Humphries was rewarded with nine games at League level where he averaged 16 disposals and five marks for a 67 average. He showed versatility by playing off half-back and through the midfield, also managing 15 scoring shots in 11 games for the Reserves.
Short: Somewhat mature-age pick, scored strongly at WAFL Reserve level

Comment: Fawcett produced a strong year at U18 level in the SANFL, kicking 32 goals from 16 games, including registering six or more scoring shots on six occasions. He averaging 16 disposals and seven marks for an average of 79, including four scores over 100. He was a little inconsistent however, going goalless on five occasions and his defensive pressure could use some help, averaging just 1.6 tackles per game. The Tigers "believe he has a lot of growth in his game" so don't hold your breath on him playing early on.
Short: Key forward with decent scoring, will need time to develop at senior level though

Comment: More of an 'upside' pick rather than raw numbers, Lual showed glimpses of his talent with ball in hand, averaging 17 disposals and 64 AF points in the Coates Talent League. He is damaging on the rebound and solid when required to defend, also showing ability to play further up the ground with some roles through the middle later in the season. Overall he might need some development before debuting, and even then, there should be other more attractive scoring options.
Short: Rebounding defender but scoring isn't great

Comment: Came roaring into draft contention after kicking 19 goals in a school footy game, Lloyd is a key forward who produced a strong season in the Coates Talent League, averaging 13 disposals and six marks for 67 AF points while also having at least two scoring shots per game. He managed two games in the VFL for Frankston near the end of the season although he failed to kick a goal and averaged just 34 AF points from limited opportunity. Hard to see him getting a game early at the Lions.
Short: Key forward at Brisbane who will need time to develop

Comment: Another mature age selection going to the Cats, Wiltshire last played in the Coates Talent League in 2021 before returning to country football, kicking 51 goals this season including a 12 goal haul. His Coates Talent League numbers from three years ago were unimpressive, though he is now playing a different position and has had plenty of time to develop his game.
Short: Mature age forward plucked from country football after a dominant few years

Comment: Murphy is a key defender who earned All-Australian honours in the U18 Champs as well as Vic Metro's MVP. Unfortunately his scoring isn't great, averaging 48 and 43 in the U18 Champs and Coates Talent League respectively, with a ceiling game of 18 disposals and eight marks for 66 AF points. Unlikely he'll be selected early on, but either way he's a pass as there are sure to be better options.
Short: Key defender with minimal scoring capacity

Comment: Moved to the backline in 2023 and earned a spot in the backline for the title-winning Allies side, averaging eight disposals, two marks, and two tackles for 31 AF points from three games. His numbers were improved for the Lions Academy, averaging 14 disposals, five marks and three tackles for a 64 average.
Short: Key defender with low scoring capacity

Comment: Capable both inside and outside through the midfield, Torrent moved his way up across the season, playing Colts in his stint prior to the U18 Champs returning to Reserve level afterward and eventually earning a debut at League level in Round 20. He prefers disposal by foot, as shown by a 4:1 kick-to-handball ratio, though he isn't afraid to get in the contest, averaging nearly five tackles per game at Reserve level.
Short: Loves to kick but also gets involved in the contest

Comment: A mature age selection, Mannagh produced a huge season in the VFL which included BOG honours in a losing Grand Final. He averaged 26 disposals and kicked 40 goals in 2023, culminating in a 27 disposal, six goal performance in the GF. Given his age and experience he should absolutely be ready to jump straight in at the top level and will be firmly in the mix for a Round 1 debut. At basement price, he seems an automatic pick if selected.
Short: Mature age draftee who dominated at VFL level

Comment: A highly athletic prospect, Jiath produced a strong second half of the season in the Coates Talent League as an intercepting defender. He averaged 64 AF points from 17 disposals, though he showed some ceiling performances later in the year with a 29 disposal, six tackle performance for 114 in the wild card round and a 26 disposal, eight mark performance for 106 in Round 13. He'll probably need a bit of development before he breaks in for a debut at the Pies.
Short: Intercept defender with inconsistent scoring, able to produce high ceiling games on occasion

Comment: A classical small forward, Anastasopoulos is dangerous around goal and able to impact the scoreboard from minimal disposal. He kicked 21.2 (!) in 11 games in the Coates Talent League, averaging 11 disposals and four tackles for 60 AF points. He struggled in the step up at the U18 Champs, kicking two goals from his three games and averaging just 7.7 disposals for an average of 38. Given his scoring profile, we should probably look elsewhere if possible.
Short: Deadly accurate small forward but scoring not great

Comment: Lorenz is an outside mid who puts up solid numbers across the board, averaging 19 disposals, and nearing five marks and five tackles for an 85 average. His game-by-game consistency in the Coates Talent League was impressive, with a low score of 69 and a high of 105, while his U18 Champs performance was also strong, again averaging 19 disposals, though his marks and tackles dropped, resulting in a 66 average.
Short: Highly consistent outside mid, able to impact forward and around the contest

Comment: Playing as a key defender and through the ruck, Zakostelsky featured 13 times in the WAFL Colts, capping his year with his 2nd ton in the GF. As a full time ruck he averaged 23 hitouts across seven games, but it was his defending that attracted attention from WA recruiters, featuring twice for WA as a key back.
Short: Scores well if rucking but limited as a defender
